{"title_page": "Cafe Bazaar", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Cafe Bazaar\n| logo                = Factsheet1.png\n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_caption       = \n| native_name         = \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631\n| native_name_lang    = fa\u0628\u0627\u0632\n\u0627\u0631\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n| former_name         = \n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry            = [[Internet]]\n[[Computer software]]\n[[Digital Application Marketplace]]\n| founded             = April 6th, 2011\n| founder             = Hessam Armandehi, Reza Mohammadi\n| hq_location         = \n| hq_location_city    = [[Tehran]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Iran]]\n| area_served         = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people          = \n| products            = \n| brands              = \n| services            = \n| owner               = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| website             = {{URL|cafebazaar.ir}}         <!-- or: | homepage = --><!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| equity              = \u20ac380 million\n}}\n'''Cafe Bazaar''' ({{lang-fa| \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631}}) is an Iranian [[android (operating system)|Android]] [[marketplace]] founded in April 2011 by Reza Mohammadi and Hessam Armandehi. In April 2019 Cafe Bazaar announced it has surpassed 40 million users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/97365/iranian-android-market-records-40-million-active-users|title=Iranian Android Market Records 40 Million Active Users|date=2019-04-09|website=Financial Tribune|language=En|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> Cafe Bazaar provides its services specifically to [[Persian language|Persian]]-speaking users<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en |title=About Us |publisher=Cafebazaar.ir |date= |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref> and offers more than 25,000 downloadable Iranian and international apps for [[Gambling|gaming]], [[social media]], messaging and other uses. It gets roughly 20 million visits a week within Iran<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/technology-startups-take-root-in-tehran-1424917952 |title=Technology Startups Take Root in Tehran |publisher=WSJ |date=2015-02-25 |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref> and its value is estimated at \u20ac380 million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Author Interviews |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2014/10/25/356646970/iranian-entrepreneurs-make-pitches-that-are-just-practice-for-now |title=Iranian Entrepreneurs Make Pitches That Are Just Practice, For Now : Parallels |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\nCafe Bazaar is by far the most popular app store among Iranians, controlling 97%<ref name=\"azernews.az\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/region/118470.html|title=How developers can make money in Iran\u2019s app market?|date=2017-09-04|website=AzerNews.az|language=en|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> of the market. Cafe Bazaar is owned by Hezardastan Information Technology Development Group which also operates Divar, a popular online classified ad service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://techrasa.com/2016/08/23/cafe-bazaar-divar-expand-afghanistan/|title=Cafe Bazaar and Divar Expand to Afghanistan|last=Jozi|first=Alireza|date=2016-08-23|website=TechRasa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> According to an April 2018 report,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://s.cafebazaar.ir/1/reports/Cafebazaar-Annual-Report-1396.pdf|title=Cafe Bazaar Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=Cafe Bazaar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> Cafe Bazaar has 36 million users, with 29 million using the platform every month and 5.3 million using it every day. In 2017, Cafe Bazaar participated in the [[Mobile World Congress|World Mobile Congress]] event in Barcelona, the world's largest mobile gathering, to introduce Iran's local mobile ecosystem resulting in many new partnerships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://techrasa.com/2017/03/03/cafe-bazaar-introduces-irans-mobile-ecosystem-mwc/|title=Cafe Bazaar Introduces Iran\u2019s Local Mobile Ecosystem at MWC|last=Azali|first=MohammadReza|date=2017-03-03|website=TechRasa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Catalog of Content ==\nNearly 160,000 applications are available on Cafe Bazaar's platform covering a wide range of uses such as education, planning, ride sharing, e-commerce, travel, lifestyle, wellness and others. According to the report, citing data compiled between March 2017 and March 2018, income from gaming apps experienced a 94% year-on-year increase. Other apps also surged 64% compared to the year which ended in March 2017. 4.7 million apps are downloaded from Cafe Bazaar every day and 7.9 million apps are sold every month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/region/118444.html|title=Sanctions push Iran develop tailored Android app stores|date=2017-09-03|website=AzerNews.az|language=en|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n=== \u064eApplications ===\nAccording to the report, citing data compiled between March 2017 and March 2018, income from gaming apps experienced a 94% year-on-year increase. Other apps also surged 64% compared to the year which ended in March 2017. 4.7 million apps are downloaded from Cafe Bazaar every day and 7.9 million apps are sold every month.\n\nAccording to Cafe Bazaar's CEO Amin Amirsharifi, in 2017, the most popular apps on Cafe Bazaar are Telegram, Instagram, [[SHAREit]] (a file transfer platform), Divar (a classified ads app) and [[Snapp (company)|Snapp]] (a taxi-hailing app).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobileworldlive.com/apps/focus-apps/qa-cafe-bazaar-discusses-iran-apps-market/|title=Q&A: Cafe Bazaar discusses Iran apps market|date=2017-10-05|website=Mobile World Live|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2018 report, the most downloaded apps between March 2017 and March 2018 are as follows: [https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n|Applications\n|Number of active Installations in the year\n|-\n|1\n|Divar (classifieds and sharing)\n|13 million+\n|-\n|2\n|Baad Saba Calendar\n|8 million+\n|-\n|3\n|Toolbox\n|6 million+\n|-\n|4\n|My Irancell (official app of Irancell)\n|6 million+\n|-\n|5\n|Snapp (ride sharing)\n|6 million+\n|-\n|6\n|App (financial services)\n|5 million +\n|-\n|7\n|Sheypoor (classifieds and sharing)\n|4 million+\n|-\n|8\n|Aparat (video sharing)\n|4 million+\n|-\n|9\n|Telewebion (video)\n|4 million+\n|-\n|10\n|My Hamrah (official app of Hamrah Aval)\n|4 million+\n|}\n\n=== Games ===\nCafe Bazaar has had much success with game downloads in the midst of the \u201craging success of mobile games\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/40291/raging-success-of-mobile-games|title=Raging Success of Mobile Games|date=2016-04-26|website=Financial Tribune|language=En|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> in Iran as demonstrated by the popularity of games like [[Clash of Clans]]. According to the 2013 survey, Iran had 18 million gamers between the ages of three and forty. Caf\u00e9 Bazaar is increasingly looking towards games to drive future revenue. Chinese developers have already staked a prominent position in the games offered by Cafe Bazaar. Their app marketplace offers games from major international developers including [[Supercell (video game company)|Supercell]], [https://www.tap4fun.com/ Tap4Fun] and [http://www.elex-tech.com/en/ Elex].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://techrasa.com/2016/04/02/cafe-bazaar-signed-a-contract-with-supercell/|title=Cafe Bazaar Signed a Contract With Supercell|last=Azali|first=MohammadReza|date=2016-04-02|website=TechRasa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of revenue generated from game users, Iran ranks third behind Turkey and Saudi Arabia in the Middle East region according to data compiled by Newzoo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newzoo.com/insights/rankings/top-100-countries-by-game-revenues/|title=Top Countries & Markets by Game Revenues|website=Newzoo|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Cafe Bazaar, there are about 120 non-Iranian publishers and developers, with over 800 apps, that offer apps through its platform. App developers receive 70% of revenue from their apps. There are local publishers that work with foreign developers to localize apps and games for a [[Persian language|Persian]]-speaking customer base.<ref name=\"azernews.az\"/>\n\n=== Media and Video ===\nIn 2018, Cafe Bazaar announced a new collaboration with local VOD and IPTV service providers like Filimo to deliver video streaming services. The new service, at its inception, largely focused on the 2018 World Cup. After that, the video content was diversified on the platform with the help of other content providers. Currently, thousands of film and television programs are provided on the platform, including all popular Iranian titles, in addition to an IPTV channel for kids.\n\n== Financial Transactions ==\nAs mobile games got more popular in Iran, Cafe Bazaar allowed In-App purchases with debit cards for popular foreign Android games. This is especially important as e-commerce is very popular in Iran and Debit Cards are the preferred system of payment. By 2015, 20% of Iranians reported shopping daily using their debit card, 24% weekly, and 28% on a monthly basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2016/04/03/as-sanctions-lift-western-companies-can-meet-a-thriving-iranian-e-commerce-industry/|title=As sanctions lift, Western companies can meet a thriving Iranian e-commerce industry|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> As of 2016, Machinarium, Clash of Kings, Brothers in Arms 3, March of Empires, Township, King's Empire and other world renown titles were participating in this mechanism. Prior to Cafe Bazaar facilitating the use of local debit cards for In-App purchases, users of foreign games like Clash of Clans, one of the most popular games in Iran, had to resort to using third-party websites were security was sometimes lacking and services were expensive.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Parent Company and Shareholders ==\nCafe Bazaar is a product of Hezardastan Information Technology Development Group that is owned by an international group of shareholders. According to the company, their shareholders are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en|title=Cafe Bazaar: About Us|website=Cafe Bazaar|archive-url=https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en|archive-date=2/12/2018|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''Name'''\n|'''Share (Percent)'''\n|-\n|Founders and managers\n|39.65\n|-\n|Employees\u2019 incentive\n|1.31\n|-\n|Rahnema Kamyaban Nokhostin Co.\n|29.92\n|-\n|Novin Andishan Sarava Pars Co.\n|19.22\n|-\n|Other legal entities\n|7.85\n|-\n|Incentive Share Committed to Employees\n|2.06\n|}\nCafe Bazaar is part of a technology scene that has developed amid \u2014and perhaps due to\u2014 international [[International sanctions|sanctions]] and strict [[censorship]] laws that have scared off global tech companies.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Considering the fact that at the time, [[Google Play]] was not accessible to the Iranian users, Cafe Bazaar launched their marketplace offering not only the viral apps you see in Google Play, but local Iranian apps making a room for Iranian startups and app developers to launch their product in their homeland.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alireza Jozi |url=http://techrasa.com/2015/06/24/how-sanctions-helped-iranian-startups-thrive/ |title=How Sanctions Helped Iranian Startups Thrive |publisher=Techrasa |date= |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Investment and Diversification ==\nIn 2018, Amsterdam-based International Internet Investment Co\u00f6peratief (IIIC) committed to investing \u20ac38 million in Cafe Bazaar's parent company, Hezardastan Information Technology Development Group, in exchange for a 10% stake. Co-Founder and Chairman Hessam Armandehi told ILNA that \u201c[o]ur management structure will remain intact after the investment. \u2026 The money will be used to develop new services including a cloud service.\u201d He added that \u201cWe are planning to turn Cafe Bazaar into a unicorn startup.\u201d The investment of the Dutch firm will facilitate Cafe Bazaar moving into new fields of innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/80615/dutch-company-to-invest-in-iran-technology-firm|title=Dutch Company to Invest in Iran Technology Firm|date=2018-01-23|website=Financial Tribune|language=En|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropic Work ==\nCafe Bazaar donated money to help rebuild a school in Revansar County, in the province of [[Kermanshah Province|Kermanshah]] that was badly affected by the 2017 earthquake that devastated parts of western Iran. Cafe Bazaar teamed up with developers from Iran and abroad to raise funds. The school was opened on November 26, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.cafebazaar.ir/1397/09/07/schoolopening|title=\u0632\u0646\u06af \u0627\u0645\u06cc\u062f \u0628\u0647 \u0635\u062f\u0627 \u062f\u0631\u0622\u0645\u062f :: \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631 {{!}} \u0648\u0628\u0644\u0627\u06af \u0631\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u062a\u0648\u0633\u0639\u0647\u200c\u062f\u0647\u0646\u062f\u06af\u0627\u0646|website=blog.cafebazaar.ir|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nCafe Bazaar has sponsored a number of competitions and events aimed at promoting digital and programming knowledge in Iran and promoting Iran's information technology industry globally. These events include the 43rd [[ACM International Collegiate Programming Contest]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://icpc.sharif.edu/2018/|title=ACM-ICPC, Asia Region, Tehran Site|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> the [[Iran Internet Programming Contest]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://icpc.sharif.edu/2018/internet-contest|title=Internet Contest {{!}} ACM-ICPC, Asia Region, Tehran Site|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> the International [https://www.bebras.org/ Bebras] Challenge on Informatics and Computational Thinking,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bebras.ir/|title=\u0628\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0633 \u2013 \u0686\u0627\u0644\u0634 \u0628\u06cc\u0646\u200c\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0633|language=fa-IR|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> and the annual Born in Iran festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.cafebazaar.ir/1397/07/21/bII3|title=\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0634\u06cc \u0627\u0632 \u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0633\u0648\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u062f\u0648\u0631\u0647 \"\u0645\u062a\u0648\u0644\u062f \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\" :: \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631 {{!}} \u0648\u0628\u0644\u0627\u06af \u0631\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u062a\u0648\u0633\u0639\u0647\u200c\u062f\u0647\u0646\u062f\u06af\u0627\u0646|website=blog.cafebazaar.ir|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Google Play]]\n* [[App Store (iOS)]]\n* [[BlackBerry World]]\n* [[List of mobile software distribution platforms]]\n* [[List of most downloaded Android applications]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://cafebazaar.ir/}}\n* [https://dgto.ir/tnq \u0627\u0631\u0632\u0634 \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u0647 \u062d\u062f\u0648\u062f \u0646\u06cc\u0645 \u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062f\u0644\u0627\u0631 \u0631\u0633\u06cc\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a]\n\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of Iran]]\n[[Category:Mobile software distribution platforms]]\n[[Category:Iranian brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Cafe Bazaar\n| logo                = Factsheet1.png\n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_caption       = \n| native_name         = \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631\n| native_name_lang    = fa\n| former_name         = \n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry            = [[Internet]]\n[[Computer software]]\n[[Digital Application Marketplace]]\n| founded             = April 6th, 2011\n| founder             = Hessam Armandehi, Reza Mohammadi\n| hq_location         = \n| hq_location_city    = [[Tehran]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Iran]]\n| area_served         = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people          = \n| products            = \n| brands              = \n| services            = \n| owner               = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| website             = {{URL|cafebazaar.ir}}         <!-- or: | homepage = --><!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| equity              = \u20ac380 million\n}}\n'''Cafe Bazaar''' ({{lang-fa| \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647 \u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631}}) is an Iranian [[android (operating system)|Android]] [[marketplace]] founded in April 2011 by Reza Mohammadi and Hessam Armandehi. In April 2019 Cafe Bazaar announced it has surpassed 40 million users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/97365/iranian-android-market-records-40-million-active-users|title=Iranian Android Market Records 40 Million Active Users|date=2019-04-09|website=Financial Tribune|language=En|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> Cafe Bazaar provides its services specifically to [[Persian language|Persian]]-speaking users<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en |title=About Us |publisher=Cafebazaar.ir |date= |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref> and offers more than 25,000 downloadable Iranian and international apps for [[Gambling|gaming]], [[social media]], messaging and other uses. It gets roughly 20 million visits a week within Iran<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/technology-startups-take-root-in-tehran-1424917952 |title=Technology Startups Take Root in Tehran |publisher=WSJ |date=2015-02-25 |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref> and its value is estimated at \u20ac380 million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Author Interviews |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2014/10/25/356646970/iranian-entrepreneurs-make-pitches-that-are-just-practice-for-now |title=Iranian Entrepreneurs Make Pitches That Are Just Practice, For Now : Parallels |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\nCafe Bazaar is by far the most popular app store among Iranians, controlling 97%<ref name=\"azernews.az\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/region/118470.html|title=How developers can make money in Iran\u2019s app market?|date=2017-09-04|website=AzerNews.az|language=en|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> of the market. Cafe Bazaar is owned by Hezardastan Information Technology Development Group which also operates Divar, a popular online classified ad service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://techrasa.com/2016/08/23/cafe-bazaar-divar-expand-afghanistan/|title=Cafe Bazaar and Divar Expand to Afghanistan|last=Jozi|first=Alireza|date=2016-08-23|website=TechRasa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> According to an April 2018 report,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://s.cafebazaar.ir/1/reports/Cafebazaar-Annual-Report-1396.pdf|title=Cafe Bazaar Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=Cafe Bazaar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> Cafe Bazaar has 36 million users, with 29 million using the platform every month and 5.3 million using it every day. In 2017, Cafe Bazaar participated in the [[Mobile World Congress|World Mobile Congress]] event in Barcelona, the world's largest mobile gathering, to introduce Iran's local mobile ecosystem resulting in many new partnerships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://techrasa.com/2017/03/03/cafe-bazaar-introduces-irans-mobile-ecosystem-mwc/|title=Cafe Bazaar Introduces Iran\u2019s Local Mobile Ecosystem at MWC|last=Azali|first=MohammadReza|date=2017-03-03|website=TechRasa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Catalog of Content ==\nNearly 160,000 applications are available on Cafe Bazaar's platform covering a wide range of uses such as education, planning, ride sharing, e-commerce, travel, lifestyle, wellness and others. According to the report, citing data compiled between March 2017 and March 2018, income from gaming apps experienced a 94% year-on-year increase. Other apps also surged 64% compared to the year which ended in March 2017. 4.7 million apps are downloaded from Cafe Bazaar every day and 7.9 million apps are sold every month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/region/118444.html|title=Sanctions push Iran develop tailored Android app stores|date=2017-09-03|website=AzerNews.az|language=en|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n=== \u064eApplications ===\nAccording to the report, citing data compiled between March 2017 and March 2018, income from gaming apps experienced a 94% year-on-year increase. Other apps also surged 64% compared to the year which ended in March 2017. 4.7 million apps are downloaded from Cafe Bazaar every day and 7.9 million apps are sold every month.\n\nAccording to Cafe Bazaar's CEO Amin Amirsharifi, in 2017, the most popular apps on Cafe Bazaar are Telegram, Instagram, [[SHAREit]] (a file transfer platform), Divar (a classified ads app) and [[Snapp (company)|Snapp]] (a taxi-hailing app).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobileworldlive.com/apps/focus-apps/qa-cafe-bazaar-discusses-iran-apps-market/|title=Q&A: Cafe Bazaar discusses Iran apps market|date=2017-10-05|website=Mobile World Live|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2018 report, the most downloaded apps between March 2017 and March 2018 are as follows: [https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n|Applications\n|Number of active Installations in the year\n|-\n|1\n|Divar (classifieds and sharing)\n|13 million+\n|-\n|2\n|Baad Saba Calendar\n|8 million+\n|-\n|3\n|Toolbox\n|6 million+\n|-\n|4\n|My Irancell (official app of Irancell)\n|6 million+\n|-\n|5\n|Snapp (ride sharing)\n|6 million+\n|-\n|6\n|App (financial services)\n|5 million +\n|-\n|7\n|Sheypoor (classifieds and sharing)\n|4 million+\n|-\n|8\n|Aparat (video sharing)\n|4 million+\n|-\n|9\n|Telewebion (video)\n|4 million+\n|-\n|10\n|My Hamrah (official app of Hamrah Aval)\n|4 million+\n|}\n\n=== Games ===\nCafe Bazaar has had much success with game downloads in the midst of the \u201craging success of mobile games\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/40291/raging-success-of-mobile-games|title=Raging Success of Mobile Games|date=2016-04-26|website=Financial Tribune|language=En|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> in Iran as demonstrated by the popularity of games like [[Clash of Clans]]. According to the 2013 survey, Iran had 18 million gamers between the ages of three and forty. Caf\u00e9 Bazaar is increasingly looking towards games to drive future revenue. Chinese developers have already staked a prominent position in the games offered by Cafe Bazaar. Their app marketplace offers games from major international developers including [[Supercell (video game company)|Supercell]], [https://www.tap4fun.com/ Tap4Fun] and [http://www.elex-tech.com/en/ Elex].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://techrasa.com/2016/04/02/cafe-bazaar-signed-a-contract-with-supercell/|title=Cafe Bazaar Signed a Contract With Supercell|last=Azali|first=MohammadReza|date=2016-04-02|website=TechRasa|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of revenue generated from game users, Iran ranks third behind Turkey and Saudi Arabia in the Middle East region according to data compiled by Newzoo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newzoo.com/insights/rankings/top-100-countries-by-game-revenues/|title=Top Countries & Markets by Game Revenues|website=Newzoo|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Cafe Bazaar, there are about 120 non-Iranian publishers and developers, with over 800 apps, that offer apps through its platform. App developers receive 70% of revenue from their apps. There are local publishers that work with foreign developers to localize apps and games for a [[Persian language|Persian]]-speaking customer base.<ref name=\"azernews.az\"/>\n\n=== Media and Video ===\nIn 2018, Cafe Bazaar announced a new collaboration with local VOD and IPTV service providers like Filimo to deliver video streaming services. The new service, at its inception, largely focused on the 2018 World Cup. After that, the video content was diversified on the platform with the help of other content providers. Currently, thousands of film and television programs are provided on the platform, including all popular Iranian titles, in addition to an IPTV channel for kids.\n\n== Financial Transactions ==\nAs mobile games got more popular in Iran, Cafe Bazaar allowed In-App purchases with debit cards for popular foreign Android games. This is especially important as e-commerce is very popular in Iran and Debit Cards are the preferred system of payment. By 2015, 20% of Iranians reported shopping daily using their debit card, 24% weekly, and 28% on a monthly basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2016/04/03/as-sanctions-lift-western-companies-can-meet-a-thriving-iranian-e-commerce-industry/|title=As sanctions lift, Western companies can meet a thriving Iranian e-commerce industry|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> As of 2016, Machinarium, Clash of Kings, Brothers in Arms 3, March of Empires, Township, King's Empire and other world renown titles were participating in this mechanism. Prior to Cafe Bazaar facilitating the use of local debit cards for In-App purchases, users of foreign games like Clash of Clans, one of the most popular games in Iran, had to resort to using third-party websites were security was sometimes lacking and services were expensive.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Parent Company and Shareholders ==\nCafe Bazaar is a product of Hezardastan Information Technology Development Group that is owned by an international group of shareholders. According to the company, their shareholders are as follows:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en|title=Cafe Bazaar: About Us|website=Cafe Bazaar|archive-url=https://cafebazaar.ir/about/?l=en|archive-date=2/12/2018|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''Name'''\n|'''Share (Percent)'''\n|-\n|Founders and managers\n|39.65\n|-\n|Employees\u2019 incentive\n|1.31\n|-\n|Rahnema Kamyaban Nokhostin Co.\n|29.92\n|-\n|Novin Andishan Sarava Pars Co.\n|19.22\n|-\n|Other legal entities\n|7.85\n|-\n|Incentive Share Committed to Employees\n|2.06\n|}\nCafe Bazaar is part of a technology scene that has developed amid \u2014and perhaps due to\u2014 international [[International sanctions|sanctions]] and strict [[censorship]] laws that have scared off global tech companies.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Considering the fact that at the time, [[Google Play]] was not accessible to the Iranian users, Cafe Bazaar launched their marketplace offering not only the viral apps you see in Google Play, but local Iranian apps making a room for Iranian startups and app developers to launch their product in their homeland.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alireza Jozi |url=http://techrasa.com/2015/06/24/how-sanctions-helped-iranian-startups-thrive/ |title=How Sanctions Helped Iranian Startups Thrive |publisher=Techrasa |date= |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Investment and Diversification ==\nIn 2018, Amsterdam-based International Internet Investment Co\u00f6peratief (IIIC) committed to investing \u20ac38 million in Cafe Bazaar's parent company, Hezardastan Information Technology Development Group, in exchange for a 10% stake. Co-Founder and Chairman Hessam Armandehi told ILNA that \u201c[o]ur management structure will remain intact after the investment. \u2026 The money will be used to develop new services including a cloud service.\u201d He added that \u201cWe are planning to turn Cafe Bazaar into a unicorn startup.\u201d The investment of the Dutch firm will facilitate Cafe Bazaar moving into new fields of innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/sci-tech/80615/dutch-company-to-invest-in-iran-technology-firm|title=Dutch Company to Invest in Iran Technology Firm|date=2018-01-23|website=Financial Tribune|language=En|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropic Work ==\nCafe Bazaar donated money to help rebuild a school in Revansar County, in the province of [[Kermanshah Province|Kermanshah]] that was badly affected by the 2017 earthquake that devastated parts of western Iran. Cafe Bazaar teamed up with developers from Iran and abroad to raise funds. The school was opened on November 26, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.cafebazaar.ir/1397/09/07/schoolopening|title=\u0632\u0646\u06af \u0627\u0645\u06cc\u062f \u0628\u0647 \u0635\u062f\u0627 \u062f\u0631\u0622\u0645\u062f :: \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631 {{!}} \u0648\u0628\u0644\u0627\u06af \u0631\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u062a\u0648\u0633\u0639\u0647\u200c\u062f\u0647\u0646\u062f\u06af\u0627\u0646|website=blog.cafebazaar.ir|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nCafe Bazaar has sponsored a number of competitions and events aimed at promoting digital and programming knowledge in Iran and promoting Iran's information technology industry globally. These events include the 43rd [[ACM International Collegiate Programming Contest]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://icpc.sharif.edu/2018/|title=ACM-ICPC, Asia Region, Tehran Site|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> the [[Iran Internet Programming Contest]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://icpc.sharif.edu/2018/internet-contest|title=Internet Contest {{!}} ACM-ICPC, Asia Region, Tehran Site|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> the International [https://www.bebras.org/ Bebras] Challenge on Informatics and Computational Thinking,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bebras.ir/|title=\u0628\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0633 \u2013 \u0686\u0627\u0644\u0634 \u0628\u06cc\u0646\u200c\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0633|language=fa-IR|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> and the annual Born in Iran festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.cafebazaar.ir/1397/07/21/bII3|title=\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u0634\u06cc \u0627\u0632 \u0628\u0631\u06af\u0632\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0633\u0648\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u062f\u0648\u0631\u0647 \"\u0645\u062a\u0648\u0644\u062f \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\" :: \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631 {{!}} \u0648\u0628\u0644\u0627\u06af \u0631\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u062a\u0648\u0633\u0639\u0647\u200c\u062f\u0647\u0646\u062f\u06af\u0627\u0646|website=blog.cafebazaar.ir|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Google Play]]\n* [[App Store (iOS)]]\n* [[BlackBerry World]]\n* [[List of mobile software distribution platforms]]\n* [[List of most downloaded Android applications]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://cafebazaar.ir/}}\n* [https://dgto.ir/tnq \u0627\u0631\u0632\u0634 \u06a9\u0627\u0641\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u062f\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u0647 \u062d\u062f\u0648\u062f \u0646\u06cc\u0645 \u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062f\u0644\u0627\u0631 \u0631\u0633\u06cc\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a]\n\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of Iran]]\n[[Category:Mobile software distribution platforms]]\n[[Category:Iranian brands]]\n", "name_user": "5.127.220.169", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cafe_Bazaar"}
{"title_page": "T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = T-cell-prolymphocytic leukemia \n| image           = Prolymphocyte.png \n| caption         = [[Prolymphocyte]] \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[Hematolopgy]], [[oncology]]\n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''T-cell-prolymphocytic leukemia (T-PLL)''' is a mature [[T-cell]] [[leukemia]] with aggressive behavior and predilection for [[blood]], [[bone marrow]], [[lymph nodes]], [[liver]], [[spleen]], and [[skin]] involvement.<ref name=\"who1\">{{cite book |author=Elaine Sarkin Jaffe, Nancy Lee Harris, World Health Organization, International Agency for Research on Cancer, Harald Stein, J.W. Vardiman |title=Pathology and genetics of tumours of haematopoietic and lymphoid tissues |publisher=IARC Press |location=Lyon |year=2001 |series=World Health Organization Classification of Tumors |volume=3 |isbn=92-832-2411-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XSKqcy7TUZUC}}</ref> T-PLL is a very rare leukemia, primarily affecting adults over the age of 30. It represents 2% of all small lymphocytic leukemias in adults.<ref name=\"mat1\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Matutes E, Brito-Babapulle V, Swansbury J, etal |title=Clinical and laboratory features of 78 cases of T-prolymphocytic leukemia |journal=Blood |volume=78 |issue=12 |pages=3269\u201374 |year=1991 |pmid=1742486 |doi=10.1182/blood.V78.12.3269.3269}}</ref> Other names include ''T-cell chronic lymphocytic leukemia'', ''\"knobby\" type of T-cell leukemia'', and ''T-prolymphocytic leukemia/T-cell lymphocytic leukemia.''<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nPeople affected by T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia typically have systemic disease at presentation, including [[hepatosplenomegaly|enlargement of the liver and spleen]], widespread [[lymphadenopathy|enlargement of the lymph nodes]], and skin infiltrates.<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\nDue to the systemic nature of this disease, leukemic cells can be found in peripheral blood, [[lymph nodes]], [[bone marrow]], [[spleen]], [[liver]], and [[skin]].<ref name=\"who1\"/>  A high lymphocyte count (> 100 x 10<sup>9</sup>/L) along with low amounts of [[anemia|red blood cells]] and [[thrombocytopenia|platelets]] in the blood are common findings. [[HTLV-1]] serologies are negative, and serum [[immunoglobin]]s are within normal limits with no [[paraproteins]] present.<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\n==Causes==\nIt is postulated that the originating cell line for this disease is a mature (post-[[thymus|thymic]]) T-cell.<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\n==Diagnosis==\n===Morphology===\n\nIn the peripheral blood, T-PLL consists of medium-sized [[lymphocytes]] with single [[nucleoli]] and [[basophilic]] [[cytoplasm]] with occasional blebs or projections. The [[Cell nucleus|nuclei]] are usually round to oval in shape, with occasional patients having cells with a more irregular nuclear outline that is similar to the cerebriform nuclear shape seen in [[S\u00e9zary syndrome]].<ref name=\"mat2\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Matutes E, Garcia Talavera J, O'Brien M, Catovsky D |title=The morphological spectrum of T-prolymphocytic leukaemia |journal=Br. J. Haematol. |volume=64 |issue=1 |pages=111\u201324 |date = September 1986|pmid=3489482 |doi= 10.1111/j.1365-2141.1986.tb07579.x|url=}}</ref> A small cell variant comprises 20% of all T-PLL cases, and the S\u00e9zary cell-like (cerebriform) variant is seen in 5% of cases.<ref name=\"mat2\"/>\n\nMarrow involvement is typically diffuse with morphology similar to what is observed in peripheral blood.<ref name=\"who1\"/> In the [[spleen]], the leukemic cell infiltrate both the [[red pulp]] and [[white pulp]], and [[lymph node]] involvement is typically diffuse through the [[paracortex]].<ref name=\"who1\"/> Skin infiltrates are seen in 20% of patients, and the infiltrates are usually dense and confined to the [[dermis]] and around the skin appendages.<ref name=\"mat1\"/>\n\n===Immunophenotype===\nT-PLL has the [[immunophenotype]] of a mature (post-thymic) T-lymphocyte, and the [[neoplastic]] cells are typically positive for pan-T antigens [[CD2]], [[CD3 (immunology)|CD3]], and [[CD7]] and negative for [[TdT]] and [[CD1a]]. The immunophenotype [[CD4]]+/[[CD8]]- is present in 60% of cases, the CD4+/CD8+ immunophenotype is present in 25%, and the CD4-/CD8+ immunophenotype is present in 15% of cases.<ref name=\"mat1\"/>\n\n===Genetic findings===\nClonal TCR gene rearrangements for the \u03b3 and \u03b4 chains are typically found. The most frequent chromosomal abnormality is the inversion of chromosome 14, specifically inv 14(q11;q32). This is found in 80% of cases, while 10% of cases show a reciprocal translocation of [[chromosome 14]] (t(14;14)(q11;q32)).<ref name=\"bri1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Brito-Babapulle V, Catovsky D |title=Inversions and tandem translocations involving chromosome 14q11 and 14q32 in T-prolymphocytic leukemia and T-cell leukemias in patients with ataxia telangiectasia |journal=Cancer Genet. Cytogenet. |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20139 |year=1991 |pmid=1913594 |doi=10.1016/0165-4608(91)90228-M}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"mal1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Maljaei SH, Brito-Babapulle V, Hiorns LR, Catovsky D |title=Abnormalities of chromosomes 8, 11, 14, and X in T-prolymphocytic leukemia studied by fluorescence in situ hybridization |journal=Cancer Genet. Cytogenet. |volume=103 |issue=2 |pages=110\u20136 |year=1998 |pmid=9614908 |doi=10.1016/S0165-4608(97)00410-X}}</ref> Also, abnormalities of [[chromosome 8]] are seen approximately 75% of patients, including idic (8p11), t(8;8)(p11-12;q12), and [[trisomy 8]].<ref name=\"sor1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sorour A, Brito-Babapulle V, Smedley D, Yuille M, Catovsky D |title=Unusual breakpoint distribution of 8p abnormalities in T-prolymphocytic leukemia: a study with YACS mapping to 8p11-p12 |journal=Cancer Genet. Cytogenet. |volume=121 |issue=2 |pages=128\u201332 |year=2000 |pmid=11063795 |doi=10.1016/S0165-4608(00)00239-9}}</ref>\n\n==Treatment==\nMost patients with T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia require immediate treatment.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Dearden CE, Matutes E, Cazin B, etal |title=High remission rate in T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia with CAMPATH-1H |journal=Blood |volume=98 |issue=6 |pages=1721\u20136 |date = September 2001|pmid=11535503 |doi= 10.1182/blood.V98.6.1721|url=http://www.bloodjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11535503}}</ref>\n\nT-cell prolymphocytic leukemia is difficult to treat, and it does not respond to most available chemotherapeutic drugs.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />  Many different treatments have been attempted, with limited success in certain patients:  [[purine analogues]] (pentostatin, fludarabine, cladribine), [[chlorambucil]], and various forms of combination [[chemotherapy regimens]], including [[CHOP|cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, prednisone]] (CHOP), etoposide, bleomycin (VAPEC-B).\n\n[[Alemtuzumab]] (Campath), an anti-CD52 [[monoclonal antibody]] that attacks white blood cells, has been used in treatment with greater success than previous options.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />  In one study of previously treated people with T-PLL, people who had a complete response to alemtuzumab survived a median of 16 months after treatment.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />\n\nSome patients who successfully respond to treatment also undergo [[stem cell transplantation]] to consolidate the response.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />\n\n==Prognosis==\nT-PLL is an extremely rare aggressive disease, and patients are not expected to live normal lifespans.  Before the recent introduction of better treatments, such as [[alemtuzumab]], the median survival time was 7.5 months after diagnosis.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />  More recently, some patients have survived five years and more, although the median survival is still low.\n\n==Epidemiology==\nAbout four men are diagnosed with this disease for every three women.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Matutes Estella | year = 1998 | title = T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia | url = http://www.moffitt.org/moffittapps/ccj/v5n1/article2.html | journal = Cancer Control  | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 19\u201324 |pmid=10761013| doi = 10.1177/107327489800500102 }}</ref>  Despite its overall rarity, it is also the most common type of mature [[T cell]] leukemia.<ref name=\"pmid15716243\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Valbuena JR, Herling M, Admirand JH, Padula A, Jones D, Medeiros LJ |title=T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia involving extramedullary sites |journal=Am. J. Clin. Pathol. |volume=123 |issue=3 |pages=456\u201364 |date = March 2005|pmid=15716243 |doi=10.1309/93P4-2RNG-5XBG-3KBE |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/501092}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| ICD10           = \n| ICD9            = \n| ICDO            = {{ICDO|9834|3}}\n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| DiseasesDB      = \n| MeshID          = D015461\n| Orphanet        = 86871\n}}\n{{Hematological malignancy histology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:T-Cell Prolymphocytic Leukemia}}\n[[Category:Acute lymphocytic leukemia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = T-cell-prolymphocytic leukemia \n| image           = Prolymphocyte.png \n| caption         = [[Prolymphocyte]] \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           = [[Hematolopgy]], [[oncology]]\n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''T-cell-prolymphocytic leukemia (T-PLL)''' is a mature [[T-cell]] [[leukemia]] with aggressive behavior and predilection for [[blood]], [[bone marrow]], [[lymph nodes]], [[liver]], [[spleen]], and [[skin]] involvement.<ref name=\"who1\">{{cite book |author=Elaine Sarkin Jaffe, Nancy Lee Harris, World Health Organization, International Agency for Research on Cancer, Harald Stein, J.W. Vardiman |title=Pathology and genetics of tumours of haematopoietic and lymphoid tissues |publisher=IARC Press |location=Lyon |year=2001 |series=World Health Organization Classification of Tumors |volume=3 |isbn=92-832-2411-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XSKqcy7TUZUC}}</ref> T-PLL is a very rare leukemia, primarily affecting adults over the age of 30. It represents 2% of all small lymphocytic leukemias in adults.<ref name=\"mat1\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Matutes E, Brito-Babapulle V, Swansbury J, etal |title=Clinical and laboratory features of 78 cases of T-prolymphocytic leukemia |journal=Blood |volume=78 |issue=12 |pages=3269\u201374 |year=1991 |pmid=1742486 |doi=10.1182/blood.V78.12.3269.3269}}</ref> Other names include ''T-cell chronic lymphocytic leukemia'', ''\"knobby\" type of T-cell leukemia'', and ''T-prolymphocytic leukemia/T-cell lymphocytic leukemia.''<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nPeople affected by T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia typically have systemic disease at presentation, including [[hepatosplenomegaly|enlargement of the liver and spleen]], widespread [[lymphadenopathy|enlargement of the lymph nodes]], and skin infiltrates.<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\nDue to the systemic nature of this disease, leukemic cells can be found in peripheral blood, [[lymph nodes]], [[bone marrow]], [[spleen]], [[liver]], and [[skin]].<ref name=\"who1\"/>  A high lymphocyte count (> 100 x 10<sup>9</sup>/L) along with low amounts of [[anemia|red blood cells]] and [[thrombocytopenia|platelets]] in the blood are common findings. [[HTLV-1]] serologies are negative, and serum [[immunoglobin]]s are within normal limits with no [[paraproteins]] present.<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\n==Causes==\nIt is postulated that the originating cell line for this disease is a mature (post-[[thymus|thymic]]) T-cell.<ref name=\"who1\"/>\n\n==Diagnosis==\n===Morphology===\n\nIn the peripheral blood, T-PLL consists of medium-sized [[lymphocytes]] with single [[nucleoli]] and [[basophilic]] [[cytoplasm]] with occasional blebs or projections. The [[Cell nucleus|nuclei]] are usually round to oval in shape, with occasional patients having cells with a more irregular nuclear outline that is similar to the cerebriform nuclear shape seen in [[S\u00e9zary syndrome]].<ref name=\"mat2\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Matutes E, Garcia Talavera J, O'Brien M, Catovsky D |title=The morphological spectrum of T-prolymphocytic leukaemia |journal=Br. J. Haematol. |volume=64 |issue=1 |pages=111\u201324 |date = September 1986|pmid=3489482 |doi= 10.1111/j.1365-2141.1986.tb07579.x|url=}}</ref> A small cell variant comprises 20% of all T-PLL cases, and the S\u00e9zary cell-like (cerebriform) variant is seen in 5% of cases.<ref name=\"mat2\"/>\n\nMarrow involvement is typically diffuse with morphology similar to what is observed in peripheral blood.<ref name=\"who1\"/> In the [[spleen]], the leukemic cell infiltrate both the [[red pulp]] and [[white pulp]], and [[lymph node]] involvement is typically diffuse through the [[paracortex]].<ref name=\"who1\"/> Skin infiltrates are seen in 20% of patients, and the infiltrates are usually dense and confined to the [[dermis]] and around the skin appendages.<ref name=\"mat1\"/>\n\n===Immunophenotype===\nT-PLL has the [[immunophenotype]] of a mature (post-thymic) T-lymphocyte, and the [[neoplastic]] cells are typically positive for pan-T antigens [[CD2]], [[CD3 (immunology)|CD3]], and [[CD7]] and negative for [[TdT]] and [[CD1a]]. The immunophenotype [[CD4]]+/[[CD8]]- is present in 60% of cases, the CD4+/CD8+ immunophenotype is present in 25%, and the CD4-/CD8+ immunophenotype is present in 15% of cases.<ref name=\"mat1\"/>\n\n===Genetic findings===\nClonal TCR gene rearrangements for the \u03b3 and \u03b4 chains are typically found. The most frequent chromosomal abnormality is the inversion of chromosome 14, specifically inv 14(q11;q32). This is found in 80% of cases, while 10% of cases show a reciprocal translocation of [[chromosome 14]] (t(14;14)(q11;q32)).<ref name=\"bri1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Brito-Babapulle V, Catovsky D |title=Inversions and tandem translocations involving chromosome 14q11 and 14q32 in T-prolymphocytic leukemia and T-cell leukemias in patients with ataxia telangiectasia |journal=Cancer Genet. Cytogenet. |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20139 |year=1991 |pmid=1913594 |doi=10.1016/0165-4608(91)90228-M}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"mal1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Maljaei SH, Brito-Babapulle V, Hiorns LR, Catovsky D |title=Abnormalities of chromosomes 8, 11, 14, and X in T-prolymphocytic leukemia studied by fluorescence in situ hybridization |journal=Cancer Genet. Cytogenet. |volume=103 |issue=2 |pages=110\u20136 |year=1998 |pmid=9614908 |doi=10.1016/S0165-4608(97)00410-X}}</ref> Also, abnormalities of [[chromosome 8]] are seen approximately 75% of patients, including idic (8p11), t(8;8)(p11-12;q12), and [[trisomy 8]].<ref name=\"sor1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Sorour A, Brito-Babapulle V, Smedley D, Yuille M, Catovsky D |title=Unusual breakpoint distribution of 8p abnormalities in T-prolymphocytic leukemia: a study with YACS mapping to 8p11-p12 |journal=Cancer Genet. Cytogenet. |volume=121 |issue=2 |pages=128\u201332 |year=2000 |pmid=11063795 |doi=10.1016/S0165-4608(00)00239-9}}</ref>\n\n==Treatment==\nMost patients with T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia require immediate treatment.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Dearden CE, Matutes E, Cazin B, etal |title=High remission rate in T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia with CAMPATH-1H |journal=Blood |volume=98 |issue=6 |pages=1721\u20136 |date = September 2001|pmid=11535503 |doi= 10.1182/blood.V98.6.1721|url=http://www.bloodjournal.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11535503}}</ref>\n\nT-cell prolymphocytic leukemia is difficult to treat, and it does not respond to most available chemotherapeutic drugs.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />  Many different treatments have been attempted, with limited success in certain patients:  [[purine analogues]] (pentostatin, fludarabine, cladribine), [[chlorambucil]], and various forms of combination [[chemotherapy regimens]], including [[CHOP|cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, prednisone]] (CHOP), etoposide, bleomycin (VAPEC-B).\n\n[[Alemtuzumab]] (Campath), an anti-CD52 [[monoclonal antibody]] that attacks white blood cells, has been used in treatment with greater success than previous options.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />  In one study of previously treated people with T-PLL, people who had a complete response to alemtuzumab survived a median of 16 months after treatment.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />\n\nSome patients who successfully respond to treatment also undergo [[stem cell transplantation]] to consolidate the response.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />\n\n==Prognosis==\nT-PLL is an extremely rare aggressive disease, and patients are not expected to live normal lifespans.  Before the recent introduction of better treatments, such as [[alemtuzumab]], the median survival time was 7.5 months after diagnosis.<ref name=\"pmid11535503\" />  More recently, some patients have survived five years and more, although the median survival is still low.\n\n==Epidemiology==\nAbout four men are diagnosed with this disease for every three women.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Matutes Estella | year = 1998 | title = T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia | url = http://www.moffitt.org/moffittapps/ccj/v5n1/article2.html | journal = Cancer Control  | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 19\u201324 |pmid=10761013| doi = 10.1177/107327489800500102 }}</ref>  Despite its overall rarity, it is also the most common type of mature [[T cell]] leukemia.<ref name=\"pmid15716243\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Valbuena JR, Herling M, Admirand JH, Padula A, Jones D, Medeiros LJ |title=T-cell prolymphocytic leukemia involving extramedullary sites |journal=Am. J. Clin. Pathol. |volume=123 |issue=3 |pages=456\u201364 |date = March 2005|pmid=15716243 |doi=10.1309/93P4-2RNG-5XBG-3KBE |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/501092}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD10          =  \n|   ICD9           =  \n|   ICDO           =  {{ICDO|9834|3}} \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = \n|   eMedicineTopic = \n|   DiseasesDB     = \n|   MeshID         = D015461 \n}}\n{{Hematological malignancy histology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:T-Cell Prolymphocytic Leukemia}}\n[[Category:Acute lymphocytic leukemia]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-cell_prolymphocytic_leukemia"}
{"title_page": "List of aviation accidents and incidents in the Channel Islands", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n\nThis article lists some of the aviation accidents and incidents in the [[Channel Islands]] from the 1910s to the 2010s.\n\n==1910s==\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|France}} In May 1917, a French seaplane, operating out of the [[Saint Peter Port]] French seaplane base, crashed, killing the pilot officer.\n\n==1930s==\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 29 June 1936, a [[de Havilland DH.84 Dragon]] ''Rozel Bay'' overshot [[Alderney Airport]]. It was landing with six passengers on board and the pilot, new to the airline, ran out of runway breaking the starboard propellor and damaging the undercarriage as he hit a bank. There were no fatalities and the aircraft flew soon after.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pinnegar |first=Edward |title=A History of Aviation in Alderney}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 31 July 1936, a [[Saro A.19 Cloud]] amphibian (registration: G-ABXW) \"Cloud of Iona\" [[1936 Jersey Air Disaster|went missing]] on a flight from [[Guernsey]] to [[Jersey]] on a stormy evening. All ten occupants died. The investigation concluded that the aircraft was forced to land in the sea due to loss of engine power, and was then swamped by the waves.<ref name=Doyle1991>{{cite book |last=Doyle |first=Neville |title=From Sea-Eagle to Flamingo: Channel Islands Airlines 1923-1939.}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 4 November 1938, a [[1938 Jersey Airport disaster|DH.86 G-ACZN \"St. Catherine's Bay\"]] crashed at St. Peter's shortly after take-off from Jersey airport, en route to [[Southampton]]. All 13 occupants were killed in addition to one person on the ground.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2009/11/09/air-disaster-of-1938/ |title=air disaster of 1938 |publisher=JEP}}</ref>\n\n==1940s==\n\nCivil flying was entirely disallowed during the [[German occupation of the Channel Islands]] from June 1940 - May 1945. However, many British and Luftwaffe aircraft crashlanded in and around the islands, with 139 fatal Allied casualties. A memorial to the Allied casualties has been erected at [[Guernsey Airport]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-27316113 |title=Guernsey WW2 airmen memorial design unveiled |publisher=BBC |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n===World War 2===\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 29 July 1940 a [[Heinkel He 111]] from ''I/KG 27'' crashed into the sea near [[Guernsey]], the crew survived.<ref name=\"GFCiaW\">{{cite book |first=George |last=Forty |title= Channel Islands At War: A German Perspective |publisher= Ian Allan Publishing  |ISBN= 978-0711030718 |page=244}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 9 August 1940 a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]F from ''I/JG 53'' crashed into a Flak position at [[Guernsey Airport]], 80% damage, 3 gunners died.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 13 August 1940 a [[Junkers Ju 87]]R of ''II/SG 2'' which had been damaged by a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] from [[No. 609 Squadron RAF]], crashed into the sea near [[Guernsey]] both crew died.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 13 August 1940 a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]E-4 of ''II/JG 53'' crashed on takeoff from [[Guernsey Airport]], 30% damage, the pilot was unhurt. The plane was left unguarded overnight and souvenir hunters stripped it. A request in the local newspaper resulted in a few hundredweight being delivered to the police station.<ref name=\"HW4042\">{{cite book |first=Herbert |last=Winterflood |title=Occupied Guernsey : July 1940-December 1942 |publisher=Guernsey Press |ISBN=978-0953916665}}</ref>{{rp|74}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 23 August 1940 a [[Junkers Ju 52]] (reference: 6324) from ''IV KGr.z.b.V. 10'' suffered mechanical failure and crashed at [[Jersey Airport]], 70% loss.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 25 September 1940, a [[Dornier Do 18]] (reference: 0881) was shot down by a [[Bristol Blenheim]] from [[No. 236 Squadron RAF]] near [[Guernsey]] 5 crew seen in dinghy.<ref>{{cite book |first=Herbert |last=Winterflood |title=Occupied Guernsey 1943-1945 |publisher= MSP Channel Islands (2005) |ISBN= 978-0953911677}}</ref>{{rp|157}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 16 October 1940, an [[Avro Anson]] (reference: N9889 MW-S) from [[No. 217 Squadron RAF]] on a photographic mission ditched during a storm west of Guernsey. The crew of 4 came ashore in [[Guernsey]] and taken as POW's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafdavidstowmoor.org/crash-log/view-1940-crash-log/ |title=Crash Log -1940 |publisher=rafdavidstowmoor.org |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 1 November 1940, a [[Dornier Do 17]]P (reference: 4086) from ''3./(F) 123'' of (Aufkl\u00e4rungsgruppe 123 a long-range reconnaissance unit) on a training flight crashed on La Rocco Tower while attempting to land at [[Jersey Airport]]. All 4 on board died and plane destroyed.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 3 November 1940, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-1 (reference: 0255) from ''1./(F) 123'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]] following a technical failure. 20% damage, crew OK.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 5 November 1940, a [[B\u00fccker B\u00fc 131]] (reference: 4494)  from ''1./(F) 123'' crashed at Rozel [[Jersey]] the parachute failed and the pilot died.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 5 November 1940, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-1 (reference: 0366) from ''3./(F) 123'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]]. 40% destroyed.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 7 November 1940, a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashed and overturned at [[Jersey Airport]]. Casualties over 20, mainly pilots who had finished a training course.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 19 November 1940, a [[Heinkel He 111]] (reference: 2768) from ''3. KGr. 100'' (pathfinder squadron) crashed following an engine fire on [[Crevichon]] near [[Jethou]] off [[Guernsey]], the full bomb load exploding, damaging some buildings on Jethou, the crew of four was killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faedfiles.com/faednet/jethou/jethou7.htm |title=Crevichon |publisher=Jethou |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/><ref>{{cite book |last=Cataroche |first=Jenny |title=The History and Archaeology of Jethou |publisher=L&C Press |ISBN=9781904332374}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 27 December 1940, a German aircraft, maybe a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashes and burns at [[Jersey Airport]]\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 30 December 1940, an [[Arado Ar 196]] (reference: 0124) from ''5. /K%FCFlGr. 196'' crashed on landing at [[Alderney]] due to bad weather.\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 16 January 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashed off St Catherines breakwater, [[Jersey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 22 January 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A from ''2 (F)/123'' (reference: 0401) crashed at [[Jersey Airport]] due to pilot error on landing, 15% damage, crew OK.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 19 February 1941, a [[Dornier Do 17]]P (reference: 4175) from ''3./(F) 123'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]]. 30% destroyed.\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 20 February 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 52]]A-5 (reference: 466) from ''5./(F) 122'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]] following damage from enemy [[Supermarine Spitfire]] fire. 25% damage. One wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luftwaffedata.co.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Aufkl._Gr._122_Feb_1941 |title=February 1941 |publisher=luftwaffedata.co.uk |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} In February 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashed at [[Jersey Airport]].\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 10 March 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]F from ''5 (F)/122'' (reference: 0390) collided at [[Jersey Airport]] suffering 50% damage with another [[Junkers Ju 88]]F-5 (F)/122, suffering 80% damage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luftwaffedata.co.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Aufkl._Gr._122_Feb_1941 |title=March 1941 |publisher=luftwaffedata.co.uk |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 14 March 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A from ''3 (F)/123'' (reference: 0559) crashed at [[La Corbi\u00e8re]] [[Jersey]], crew KIA. 100% loss.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 11/12 April 1941, a [[Hawker Hurricane]] on a night intruder operation ran out of fuel, the pilot bailed out and landed on [[Lihou]] [[Guernsey]] and became a prisoner of war.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tomahawkfilms.com/blog/?p=6114 |title=A Hurricane Downed over Guernsey..! |publisher=tomahawkfilms |accessdate=22 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103700/http://tomahawkfilms.com/blog/?p=6114 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Ibeg\">{{cite book |first=William |last=Bell |title=I beg to report |publisher=Bell (1995) |ISBN=978-0952047919}}</ref>{{rp|93}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 3 October 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-5 collided with another Ju 88 at [[Jersey Airport]], crew OK.\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 29 December 1941, a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]F-2 crashed at [[Saint Ouen, Jersey]] following engine failure, pilot OK.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 2 January 1942, an aircraft crashed in Bouley Bay [[Jersey]] after being shot down by an RAF plane.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 24 June 1942, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]]A-2 (reference: 5291) from ''III. /JG 2'' was rammed by a landing aircraft at [[Guernsey Airport]]. 30% damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 24 October 1942, an [[Avro Lancaster]] from ''207 Sqdn'' came down 10 miles north of [[Guernsey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 2 November 1942, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] from ''234 Sqdn'', came down close to [[Alderney]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 18 November 1942, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] Vb (reference: EN830), was hit by Flak over France and crash landed on [[Jersey]] in a turnip field. The [[Free French]] pilot waited with locals for the Germans to arrive and was captured.<ref>{{cite book |first=John |last=Lewis |title=A Doctor\u2019s Occupation |publisher= Starlight Publishing (1997) |ISBN= 978-0952565918}}</ref>{{rp|91}} The aircraft was recovered and freighted to [[Germany]] where the aircraft was tested using a German engine designed for a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://defenceoftherealm.wordpress.com/2014/11/17/the-franken-spitfire/ |title=The Franken-Spitfire |publisher=defenceoftherealm |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717055850/https://defenceoftherealm.wordpress.com/2014/11/17/the-franken-spitfire/ |archive-date=17 July 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 23 November 1942, an [[Avro Lancaster]] (reference: W4107) from ''[[No. 49 Squadron RAF]]'', crash-landed in the field opposite Seigneurie farm on [[Sark]], having run out of fuel. They thought they were landing in the Isle of Wight. All the crew were survivors, other crew having bailed out over France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.49squadron.co.uk/personnel_index/detail/Singleton_EJ |title=22/23 November, 1942; STUTTGART: |publisher=49 Squadron Association |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Marshall |first=Michael |publisher=Paramount-Lithoprint |title=Hitler envaded Sark |isbn= |year=1967}}</ref>{{rp|22}} <ref name=GFCiaW/><ref name=WFTLR/>{{rp|135}}\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 7 December 1942, a [[Westland Whirlwind (reference P6987)]] from [[No. 263 Squadron RAF]] crashed, after flying through heavy flak, south of [[Jersey]] after attacking shipping in St. Helier harbour.<ref name=\"Whirlwind\">{{cite web |url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/laurieburley/jeff/pdfs/air271550history42.pdf |title=NO. 263 SQUADRON. |publisher=ntlworld.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125833/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/laurieburley/jeff/pdfs/air271550history42.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Foreman |first=John |title=RAF fighter command victory claims Jan 41-Jun 43 |publisher=Red Kite |ISBN=978-0954620158 }}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/><ref name=WFTLR/>{{rp|135}}\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 7 December 1942, a [[Westland Whirlwind (reference P7105)]] from ''[[No. 263 Squadron RAF]]'' piloted by the Sqdn Leader was hit by flak and ditched south of [[Jersey]] after attacking shipping. The pilot was killed.<ref name=\"Whirlwind\"/><ref name=WFTLR/>{{rp|135}}\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 25 January 1943, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] from ''[[No. 541 Squadron RAF]]'' came down close to [[Guernsey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 10 April 1943, a [[Vickers Wellington]] from ''431 Sqdn'', came down in [[Saint Ouen, Jersey]] bay.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 13 June 1943, a [[Lockheed Ventura]] (reference: AE937 SB-E) from ''[[No. 464 Squadron RAAF]]'' was shot down by a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] close to [[Guernsey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafdavidstowmoor.org/crash-log/view-1943-crash-log/ |title=1943 log |publisher=rafdavidstowmoor.org |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 13 June 1943, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] II from ''[[No. 276 Squadron RAF]]'' was shot down by a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] and crashed, the pilot paddled ashore in [[Jersey]].\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 13 June 1943, a seaplane crashed north of [[Jersey]] on takeoff, after rescuing downed British pilot, crew hurt.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 15 June 1943, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] (reference: BR319 YQ-C) from [[No. 616 Squadron RAF]], on an anti shipping patrol, crashed north of [[Sark]]<ref name=\"M483\" >{{cite web|url=http://funautical.blogspot.com/2011/04/m-class-minesweeper-m483.html |title=15 June 1943 |publisher=funautical.blogspot.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 15 June 1943, a [[Westland Whirlwind (fighter)|Westland Whirlwind]] (reference: P7000) from [[No. 263 Squadron RAF]] exploded in flames and crashed, after sinking a German Minesweeper M483, north of [[Sark]]<ref name=\"M483\" />\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 15 June 1943, a [[Dornier Do 18]] seaplane crashes on takeoff at [[Saint Helier]] [[Jersey]], the Pilot broke both legs.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 25 July 1943, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] A-4 (reference: 703) from 1. /NAGr. 13 was damaged following engine trouble. 20% damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 14 August 1943, a [[Heinkel He 111]] was shot down by a[[Westland Whirlwind (fighter)]] from [[No. 263 Squadron RAF]] north of [[Guernsey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eregbaker.info/ww2_1943.htm |title=14 August 1943 |publisher=eregbaker |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 23 August 1943, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] A-3 (reference: 304) from ''2. NAGr./13'' was shot down by friendly flak over [[Herm]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 7 September 1943, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] A-3 (reference: 351) from ''2. /NAGr. 12'' Overturned on landing due to pilot error. 75% damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 31 December 1943, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] IIRC \"Speed Ball\" from 511th BS of the 351st Bomb Groupcrashed west of [[Guernsey]] 8 KIA, Two were picked up next morning and made POW's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_mia_aircraft.php?acgroup_id=49&mission_date=1943-12-31 |title=#42-29877 - B-17F |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_one_acgroup.php?acgroup_id=49 |title=42-29877 |publisher=8thafhs.com}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 31 December 1943, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] IIRC \"Piccadilly Commando\" from 508th BS of the 351st Bomb Group ditched west of [[Guernsey]] 11 were rescued from a reef and became POW's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_mia_aircraft.php?acgroup_id=49&mission_date=1943-12-31 |title=#42-29630 - B-17F |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_one_acgroup.php?acgroup_id=49 |title=42-29630 |publisher=8thafhs.com}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 27/28 January 1944, an [[Avro Lancaster]] from 61 Sqdn crashed north of [[Guernsey]] <ref name=\"aircrew\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.aircrewremembered.com/list-of-pages-relating-to-1939-1945.html |title=Allied Archive Reports relating to 1939 - 1945 |publisher=aircrewremembered.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 7 February 1944, a [[North American P-51 Mustang|Mustang P-51B]] of the ''354th Pioneer Mustang Group'', 355th Fighter Squadron, 9th US Army Air Force, escorting bombers back from a raid on Germany was badly damaged and off course when he was shot down by flak over [[Saint Ouen, Jersey]]. The pilot bailed out and was injured on landing then captured, becoming a prisoner of war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theislandwiki.org/index.php/Mustang_crashes_in_St_Ouen%27s_Bay |title=Mustang crashes in St Ouen's Bay |publisher=theIslandwiki |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 28 February 1944, a [[Hawker Typhoon]] from [[No. 247 Squadron RAF]] came down close to [[Guernsey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 7 March 1944, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]]A-4 (reference: 7099) from ''9./JG 2'' crashed at La Ponchez, [[Castel, Guernsey]] Pilot KIA.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 19 March 1944, a [[Heinkel He 177]] was shot down by a [[Bristol Beaufighter]] SW of [[Guernsey]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 23 March 1944, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] was shot up as it came in to land at [[Guernsey Airport]], slight damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} In April 1944, a [[Junkers Ju 88]] was shot down by a night fighter off [[Alderney]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 6 April 1944, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-4 crashed at Eden Chapel, St Martin [[Jersey]] Shot down in error by flak Crew x 4 KIA.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 23 April 1944, an unknown aircraft washed ashore La Rocque [[Jersey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 14/15 May 1944, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-2 of ''I/KG 2'' was shot down by a [[Bristol Beaufighter]] from [[No. 604 Squadron RAF]], crashing into the sea off [[Guernsey]], the crew bailed out and was rescued.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] In June 1944 a carrier borne [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]] crashed after being hit by flak on the beach north of [[Herm]] The pilot became a prisoner of war.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 2 June 1944, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] (reference: MB843) from [[No. 41 Squadron RAF]] on an early morning shipping reconnaissance to Peter Point, Guernsey, then on to St Malo. Shot down by Flak from Brehon Tower near Guernsey. Hit in the radiator. The American RAFVR pilot bailed out 4 to 6 miles northeast of Guernsey and became a POW.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=90247 |title=02-JUN-1944 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 5 June 1944, a [[Hawker Typhoon]] from ''439 Sqdn'' crashed close to the [[Saint Peter Port]] harbour mouth.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 7 June 1944, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] reference: MB881) from [[No. 41 Squadron RAF]] escorting Typhoons on a shipping strike against [[Saint Peter Port]], it was hit by flak. The pilot bailed out of the aircraft which crashed into the sea SE [[Sark]], attempted recovery failed and he did not survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=90254 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 8 June 1944 a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] \"Our Captain\" from [[534th Bombardment Squadron]], part of 381 BG, on mission 131 was hit by flak and losing height ditched 30 miles west of [[Jersey]]. Two [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s located the crew in their rafts, followed by a [[Vickers Wellington]] which dropped a motor boat by parachute, enabling the crew to make their safe escape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.armyairforces.com/381st-Bombardment-Group-Missions-and-News-Coverage-m232309-p15.aspx |title=381st Bombardment Group Mission #131 \u2013 La Frilliere (near Tours), France (6/8/44) |publisher=armyairforces.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 11 June 1944, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] crashed five miles north west of Grand Havre, [[Guernsey]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://guernseypress.com/news/2014/05/30/fisherman-pulls-bombers-propeller-from-sea-bed/ |title=Fisherman pulls bomber\u2019s propeller from  sea bed |publisher=Guernsey Press |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=#42-97693 - B-17G |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 14 June 1944, a [[Hawker Typhoon]] (registered: MN661) from ''263 squadron'' crashed on [[Jersey]], the Belgian [[Henri Gonay|pilot]] was killed.<ref name=\"aircrew\" /><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 19 June 1944, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] F \"Idiot's Delight\" was hit by Flak from [[Alderney]] and ditched in the sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=#42-30301 - B-17F |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 20 June 1944, a [[Heinkel He 111]] crashed in flames at Samar\u00e8s [[Jersey]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 21 June 1944 a German bomber was hit by flak from a St Peter Port flak ship and crashed, the crew of 5 all died.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 17 July 1944 a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] G from [[545th Bombardment Squadron]] part of 384 BG, crash landed, en route to France, in [[Guernsey]]. The aircraft was salvaged on 12 June 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=#43-37971 - B-17G |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 27 July 1944, an [[Avro Lancaster]] crashed into the sea east of Essex Castle. No boat was sent out from Braye harbour and no assistance was provided to try rescuing the crew.<ref name=\"WFTLR\">{{cite book |last= Fowler |first=Will |title=The Last Raid: The Commandos, Channel Islands and Final Nazi Raid |publisher=The History Press |ISBN=978-0750966375}}</ref>{{rp|136}}\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 9/10 August 1944, a [[Short Stirling]] (reference:EF256) from ''620 Sqdn'' on Operation Ditcher, ditched into the sea after being hit by anti-aircraft fire between [[Jersey]] and the French coast. The crew of 7 survived but 2 paratroopers from 3[[Special Air Service|SAS]] drowned.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://harringtonmuseum.org.uk/Aircraft%20lost%20on%20Allied%20Forces%20Special%20Duty%20Operations.pdf/ |title=Aircraft lost on Allied Force\u2019s Special Duty Operations & Associated Roll of Honour |publisher=harringtonmuseum.org.uk |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919065451/http://www.harringtonmuseum.org.uk/Aircraft%20lost%20on%20Allied%20Forces%20Special%20Duty%20Operations.pdf |archive-date=19 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 30 October 1944, a [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain]] already in trouble due to tech problems as it passed low over [[Jersey]] with its landing lights on as a sign of distress. Distress flares were dropped and German flak held off for a while. However, as it flew over the north coast a 20mm flak battery opened up and the plane crashed into the sea near to a small harbour. There was only one survivor.<ref>cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?139130 |name=Douglas C-47 Dakota (+1944) |publisher= wrecksite.eu |accessdate=27 Aug 2015</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] 7 January 1945, a [[Lockheed P-38 Lightning]] crashed into the cliffs at Beauport, SW of [[Jersey]], the wounded pilot, Lt Moutray, was rescued from St Brelades Bay.<ref>{{cite book |first=Joe |last=Mi\u00e8re |title=Never to be forgotten |publisher=Channel Island Publishing |ISBN=978-0954266981}}</ref>{{rp|120}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n===Post War===\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 13 June 1945, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] (reference: P-47D) from [[544th Bombardment Squadron]], part of 384th BG, being used as a transport for demobilized personnel, suffered a landing accident at [[Guernsey Airport]] with damage rated as level 3 on a scale of 0\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=1945-06-13 |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} 14 June 1947, an [[Airspeed Consul]], (registration: G-AHMC), operated by [[Westminster Airways]] crashed on landing at [[Jersey Airport]]. The aircraft was repaired and remained airworthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abpic.co.uk/photo/1115309/ |title=Airspeed AS.65 Consul, G-AHMC |publisher=abpic.co.uk |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1950s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 5 February 1951 an [[Avro Anson]] 652A (registration: G-AIXZ) undershot the [[Jersey Airport]] on approaching in fog. The aircraft was carrying national newspapers. The pilot and co-pilot survived but the aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=28298 |title=05-FEB-1951 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:DH.89A Rapide G-AGWR Morton AS RWY 16.07.50 edited-2.jpg|thumb|Rapide G-AGWR]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} In 1951 a [[de Havilland Dragon Rapide]] DH89A (registration: G-AGWR) operated by [[Morton Air Services]], overshot the runway and ended up near the Airport boundary. The aircraft survived and was subsequently re-registered in Norway, and after that, in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oy-reg.dk/register/2355.html |title=OY-DYA |publisher=oy-reg.dk}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 15 September 1954, a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Short Sunderland]] MR.5 (registration: PP122) hit a submerged rock on landing causing a rupture in the hull. It sank at [[Saint Peter Port]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19540915-0 |title=15 September 1954 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 2 November 1957, a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Vickers Valetta]] T.3 (registration: WJ470) hit an embankment and a building, causing the undercarriage to collapse on landing at [[Guernsey Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19571102-2 |title=Saturday 2 November 1957 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 15 August 1958, a [[Jersey Airlines]] [[de Havilland Heron]] (registration: G-AMYU) crash-landed on the grass next to the runway at Guernsey Airport and stopped on the road. Sole pilot was uninjured. Aircraft damaged beyond repair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19580815-2 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1960s==\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 1 November 1961, a [[Silver City Airways]] [[Bristol Freighter]] Coming from [[Cherbourg \u2013 Maupertus Airport]] crashed on aborting approach, due to malfunctioning of the automatic pitch coarsening unit of the starboard propeller, killing the two pilots with the other 8 occupants surviving.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19611101-0 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 26 September 1963, a [[British United Air Ferries]] [[Bristol Superfreighter]] (registration:G-AMWA) overran runway 28 at Guernsey Airport after engine problems. None of the 3 crew and 1 passenger was injured but the aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19630924-0 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 14 April 1965, [[British United Airways Flight 1030X]] [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|Douglas Dakota]] (registration:G-ANTB) crashed near [[Jersey Airport]] after a flight from [[Paris]], killing 27 passengers and crew of the 28 people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19650414-0&lang=en |title=14 April 1965 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 26 August 1966, a private [[Piper PA-20 Pacer|Piper PA-22-160]], (registration:G-ARXK) stalled while turning on its final approach to the aerodrome, crashing into the sea, 200 yards from Alderney, where the pilot and two passengers drowned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://143.95.41.247/wikibase/wiki.php?id=82736 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 29 May 1969, a [[United States Air Force]], [[Lockheed Hercules]] (registration:63-7789) on an illegal flight that took off from [[RAF Mildenhall]] was allegedly shot down by two [[F-100 Super Sabre]] aircraft 30 miles north of [[Alderney]], killing the only pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19690523-2&lang=en |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1970s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 6 August 1970, a [[Beagle B.206]], (registration: G-AVAM) crashed at Corbi\u00e8re after taking off from [[Jersey Airport]], killing the pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/11-1972-g-avam-6-august-1970 |title=11/1972 G-AVAM, 6 August 1970 |publisher=gov.uk |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 24 December 1974, [[British Island Airways]] Flight 185, a [[Handley Page Dart Herald]], (registration: G-BBXJ) was in a landing accident at [[Jersey Airport]] after a flight from [[Southampton]]. None of the 53 passengers and crew were harmed in the accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19741224-0 |title=Tuesday 24 December 1974 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 14 September 1975, a [[Vickers Viscount]] on a charter flight from East Midlands (registration: G-AZNH) made a heavy landing that caused the nose wheel to collapse. None of the 78 passengers or crew were harmed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vickersviscount.net/Index/VickersViscount342History.aspx |title=14 September 1975 |publisher=vickersviscount.net}}</ref>\n\n==1980s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 1 October 1980, a private [[Cessna Citation]] (registration: G-BPCP) crashed on approach to [[Jersey Airport]], killing the only pilot who was on a flight from [[Cardiff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/4-1982-cessna-citation-500-g-bpcp-1-october-1980 |title= 4/1982 Cessna Citation 500, G-BPCP, 1 October 1980 |publisher=GOV.UK |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 18 September 1981, a [[Jersey European Airways]] Flight 245 [[Britten-Norman Islander]] (registration: G-BDNP) on a flight from [[Jersey Airport]] to [[Guernsey Airport]] crashed on approach when one of the engines stopped. The pilot tried to land at Guernsey Airport but failed and then attempted to land in a field but crashed into a stone wall. None of the 9 passengers or crew were killed in the accident, however the pilot was badly injured. The pilot had intended to fly a version of the Islander with fuel tanks on the tips of the wings, but due to technical problems took another plane. Thus the engine ran out of fuel, stopped and caused the accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19810918-2 |title= accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 3 October 1981, a private fight [[Partenavia P.68]] (registration: EC-DHE) on a flight from [[Cardiff Airport]] to [[Alicante\u2013Elche Airport]] Aircraft was on a night IFR flight when one of the engines failed. Pilot could not maintain height and eventually crashed into the sea 5m SE off Guernsey. (The aircraft was never found) None of the 5 occupants survived.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=1076 |title= ASN Wikibase Occurrence # 1076 |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 16 September 1982, a private fight [[Wassmer WA-40|Wassmer WA-41]] (reference: G-BAGM) crashed into the sea 20 miles north of [[Alderney]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airport-data.com/aircraft/G-BAGM.html |title= G-BAGM |publisher=airport-data.com |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1990s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 23 May 1995, a [[Brymon Airways]] [[Bombardier Dash 8]] (registration: G-BRYJ) tail struck the runway 27 at [[Jersey Airport]]. The incident caused some damage to the tail of the aircraft. None of the 4 crew and 44 passengers were injured in the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/De%20Havilland%20Canada%20DHC-8-311%20Dash%208,%20G-BRYJ%2007-95.pdf |title=De Havilland Canada DHC-8-311 Dash8, G-BTYJ |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 7 December 1997, an [[AirUK]] F-27-500F (registration: G-BNCY) a flight from [[Southampton Airport]] to [[Guernsey Airport]] was involved in a landing accident at Guernsey Airport. The aircraft overran runway 27 while landing in high (34 kt) crosswinds and came to rest in an adjacent field with its left landing gear collapsed. There were no injuries among the 50 passengers and 4 crew. (The aircraft was damaged beyond repair and subsequently written off.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/publications/formal_reports/4_1999_g_bncy.cfm |title=Report No: 4/1999. Report on the accident to Fokker F27-500, G-BNCY, at Guernsey Airport, Channel Islands on 7 December 1997 |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 12 June 1998, a private [[Piper PA-31 Navajo]] (registration: CN-TFP) on a flight from [[Tangier]] to [[Iceland]]. The pilot was going to refuel in [[France]] but kept on flying to Guernsey. As the aircraft was over the Channel islands the aircraft ran out of fuel and the pilot ditched the aircraft into the sea just north-west of [[Jersey]]. The accident killed the only pilot on the aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/publications/formal_reports/2_1999_cn_tfp.cfm |title=Report No: 2/1999. Report on the accident to Piper PA-31-350, CN-TFP, north-west of Jersey, Channel Islands on 12 June 1998 |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 12 January 1999, a [[Channel Express]] F-27-600F (registration: G-CHNL) cargo flight from [[London Luton Airport]] to [[Guernsey Airport]] was incorrectly loaded affecting centre of gravity, stalled on approach to the airport, crashed, and caught fire. The fire spread to two nearby homes, killing the pilots and injuring one person on the ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19990112-0 |title=Report accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 5 June 2001, a [[Channel Express]] cargo flight from [[Jersey Airport]] to [[Bournemouth Airport]] but just minutes after takeoff engine one caught fire. The [[Fokker F-27 Friendship]] landed back at Jersey and none of the 3 crew were injured.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20010605-0 | work=Aviation Safety Network | title= 5 Jun 2001 | accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} On 13 October 2001, a [[Europa XS]] 912 light aircraft, registered G-BWGH flying from [[Jersey Airport]] suffered engine failure and crash landed on [[Little Sark]]. The two occupants were uninjured. The aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=173880 | work=Aviation Safety Network | title=13 Oct 2001 | accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 8 March 2006, a HS748 Series 2a registered G-BVOV overran the runway at [[Guernsey Airport]]. There were no injuries. The cause of the accident was that the flight crew did not operate the propeller controls correctly, meaning that less drag was created than would have been had the controls been operated correctly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/publications/formal_reports/6_2008_g_bvov.cfm |title=Report on the serious incident to Hawker Siddeley HS 748 Series 2A, G-BVOV at Guernsey Airport, Channel Islands on 8 March 2006 |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> The aircraft body now rests in a quarry in Capernwray, Lancashire where it is used by divers.\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 23 August 2009, a private [[Piper Saratoga]] (registration: G-BTCA) crashed due to turbulence caused by nearby cliffs on approach to [[Alderney Airport]]. The pilot and 3 passengers sustained minor injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/Piper%20PA-32R-300%20Cherokee%20Lance,%20G-BTCA%2002-10.pdf |title=Piper PA-32R-300 Cherokee Lance, g-BTCA |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n==2010s==\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 12 November 2011, a [[Piper PA-28 Cherokee|Piper PA-28-181 Archer II]] (registration: G-BXRG) owned by Alderney Flying Training Ltd. ditched in the sea near the Casquettes, 25 miles northwest of Alderney. The reason for the accident is not yet known. Of the two occupants in the aircraft, the passenger was rescued by a merchant ship. The pilot has not been found.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-15710937 | work=BBC News | title=Alderney aircraft crash: Search called off for man | date=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 27 March 2012, a [[Britten-Norman Trislander]] BN2A MK.III-2 (registration: G-BDTO) owned by Aurigny Air Services on a flight from [[Alderney Airport]] to [[Southampton]] suffered an engine failure, the aircraft returned safely to [[Alderney]] .<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/bn2a-mk-iii-2-trislander-g-bdto-27-march-2012 | work=GOV.UK | title=BN2A MK.III-2 Trislander, G-BDTO, 27 March 2012 | accessdate=23 Aug 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 16 June 2012, an [[ATR 42]] (registration: G-DRFC) owned by [[Blue Islands]] suffered an undercarriage failure on landing. No one was hurt but the aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-jersey-18476461 |title=Jersey Airport Blue Island plane crash probe begins |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 3 November 2013, a [[Britten-Norman Islander]] BN2B-21 (registration: G-CIAS) owned by Channel Islands Air Search on a search and rescue mission flight from [[Guernsey Airport]] suffered fuel problems resulting in a crash landing on the north coast of [[Jersey]]. There were no injuries.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/s8-2013-bn2b-21-islander-3-november-2013 | work=GOV.UK | title=S8/2013 BN2B-21 Islander,, 3 November 2013 | accessdate= 23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 17 June 2014, a [[SOCATA TB family|Socata TB10]] (registration: G-POPI) taking off from [[Guernsey Airport]] suffered a mechanical failure and struck a greenhouse shortly after becoming airborne. The aircraft was written off. There were no injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-27926178 |title=Guernsey plane crash pilot 'lucky to be alive' |publisher=Guernsey press |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 21 January 2019, a [[Piper PA-46]] (registration: N264DB) disappeared from radar screens and [[2019 Piper PA-46 Malibu crash|crashed]] near [[Les Casquets]], 8 miles north-west of [[Alderney]]. Argentinian footballer [[Emiliano Sala]] was aboard the aircraft, which was flying from [[Nantes Atlantique Airport|Nantes]] to [[Cardiff Airport|Cardiff]]. The wreckage of the aircraft was found thirteen days later on the seabed at a depth of 220 feet (67 m). On 7 February, Sala's body was recovered from the wreckage. No trace of the pilot was found.\n\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*Doyle, Neville. 1991. From Sea-Eagle to Flamingo: Channel Islands Airlines 1923\u20131939. {{ISBN|1-85421-103-X}}\n*{{cite book | last = Pinnegar | first = Edward  | pages = 128 |year = July 2010 |title = A History of Aviation in Alderney |publisher = Amberley Publishing, Stroud |isbn = 978-1-84868-981-7 }}\n\n{{Guernsey topics |state=collapsed}}\n{{Jersey topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aviation Accident And Incidents In The Channel Islands}}\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in the Channel Islands| ]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Channel Islands during World War II]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom aviation-related lists|Channel Islands accidents]]\n[[Category:Lists of aviation accidents and incidents|Channel Islands]]\n[[Category:History of Guernsey]]\n[[Category:History of Jersey]]\n[[Category:History of Alderney]]\n[[Category:Channel Islands-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n\nThis article lists some of the aviation accidents and incidents in the [[Channel Islands]] from the 1910s to the 2010s.\n\n==1910s==\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|France}} In May 1917, a French seaplane, operating out of the [[Saint Peter Port]] French seaplane base, crashed, killing the pilot officer.\n\n==1930s==\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 29 June 1936, a [[de Havilland DH.84 Dragon]] ''Rozel Bay'' overshot [[Alderney Airport]]. It was landing with six passengers on board and the pilot, new to the airline, ran out of runway breaking the starboard propellor and damaging the undercarriage as he hit a bank. There were no fatalities and the aircraft flew soon after.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pinnegar |first=Edward |title=A History of Aviation in Alderney}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 31 July 1936, a [[Saro A.19 Cloud]] amphibian (registration: G-ABXW) \"Cloud of Iona\" [[1936 Jersey Air Disaster|went missing]] on a flight from [[Guernsey]] to [[Jersey]] on a stormy evening. All ten occupants died. The investigation concluded that the aircraft was forced to land in the sea due to loss of engine power, and was then swamped by the waves.<ref name=Doyle1991>{{cite book |last=Doyle |first=Neville |title=From Sea-Eagle to Flamingo: Channel Islands Airlines 1923-1939.}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 4 November 1938, a [[1938 Jersey Airport disaster|DH.86 G-ACZN \"St. Catherine's Bay\"]] crashed at St. Peter's shortly after take-off from Jersey airport, en route to [[Southampton]]. All 13 occupants were killed in addition to one person on the ground.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2009/11/09/air-disaster-of-1938/ |title=air disaster of 1938 |publisher=JEP}}</ref>\n\n==1940s==\n\nCivil flying was entirely disallowed during the [[German occupation of the Channel Islands]] from June 1940 - May 1945. However, many British and Luftwaffe aircraft crashlanded in and around the islands, with 139 fatal Allied casualties. A memorial to the Allied casualties has been erected at [[Guernsey Airport]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-27316113 |title=Guernsey WW2 airmen memorial design unveiled |publisher=BBC |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n===World War 2===\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 29 July 1940 a [[Heinkel He 111]] from ''I/KG 27'' crashed into the sea near [[Guernsey]], the crew survived.<ref name=\"GFCiaW\">{{cite book |first=George |last=Forty |title= Channel Islands At War: A German Perspective |publisher= Ian Allan Publishing  |ISBN= 978-0711030718 |page=244}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 9 August 1940 a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]F from ''I/JG 53'' crashed into a Flak position at [[Guernsey Airport]], 80% damage, 3 gunners died.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 13 August 1940 a [[Junkers Ju 87]]R of ''II/SG 2'' which had been damaged by a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] from [[No. 609 Squadron RAF]], crashed into the sea near [[Guernsey]] both crew died.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 13 August 1940 a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]E-4 of ''II/JG 53'' crashed on take off from [[Guernsey Airport]], 30% damage, the pilot was unhurt. The plane was left unguarded overnight and souvenir hunters stripped it. A request in the local newspaper resulted in a few hundredweight being delivered to the police station.<ref name=\"HW4042\">{{cite book |first=Herbert |last=Winterflood |title=Occupied Guernsey : July 1940-December 1942 |publisher=Guernsey Press |ISBN=978-0953916665}}</ref>{{rp|74}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 23 August 1940 a [[Junkers Ju 52]] (reference: 6324) from ''IV KGr.z.b.V. 10'' suffered mechanical failure and crashed at [[Jersey Airport]], 70% loss.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 25 September 1940, a [[Dornier Do 18]] (reference: 0881) was shot down by a [[Bristol Blenheim]] from [[No. 236 Squadron RAF]] near [[Guernsey]] 5 crew seen in dinghy.<ref>{{cite book |first=Herbert |last=Winterflood |title=Occupied Guernsey 1943-1945 |publisher= MSP Channel Islands (2005) |ISBN= 978-0953911677}}</ref>{{rp|157}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 16 October 1940, an [[Avro Anson]] (reference: N9889 MW-S) from [[No. 217 Squadron RAF]] on a photographic mission ditched during a storm west of Guernsey. The crew of 4 came ashore in [[Guernsey]] and taken as POW's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafdavidstowmoor.org/crash-log/view-1940-crash-log/ |title=Crash Log -1940 |publisher=rafdavidstowmoor.org |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 1 November 1940, a [[Dornier Do 17]]P (reference: 4086) from ''3./(F) 123'' of (Aufkl\u00e4rungsgruppe 123 a long-range reconnaissance unit) on a training flight crashed on La Rocco Tower while attempting to land at [[Jersey Airport]]. All 4 on board died and plane destroyed.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 3 November 1940, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-1 (reference: 0255) from ''1./(F) 123'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]] following a technical failure. 20% damage, crew OK.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 5 November 1940, a [[B\u00fccker B\u00fc 131]] (reference: 4494)  from ''1./(F) 123'' crashed at Rozel [[Jersey]] the parachute failed and the pilot died.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 5 November 1940, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-1 (reference: 0366) from ''3./(F) 123'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]]. 40% destroyed.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 7 November 1940, a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashed and overturned at [[Jersey Airport]]. Casualties over 20, mainly pilots who had finished a training course.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 19 November 1940, a [[Heinkel He 111]] (reference: 2768) from ''3. KGr. 100'' (pathfinder squadron) crashed following an engine fire on [[Crevichon]] near [[Jethou]] off [[Guernsey]], the full bomb load exploding, damaging some buildings on Jethou, the crew of four was killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faedfiles.com/faednet/jethou/jethou7.htm |title=Crevichon |publisher=Jethou |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/><ref>{{cite book |last=Cataroche |first=Jenny |title=The History and Archaeology of Jethou |publisher=L&C Press |ISBN=9781904332374}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 27 December 1940, a German aircraft, maybe a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashes and burns at [[Jersey Airport]]\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 30 December 1940, an [[Arado Ar 196]] (reference: 0124) from ''5. /K%FCFlGr. 196'' crashed on landing at [[Alderney]] due to bad weather.\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 16 January 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashed off St Catherines breakwater, [[Jersey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 22 January 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A from ''2 (F)/123'' (reference: 0401) crashed at [[Jersey Airport]] due to pilot error on landing, 15% damage, crew OK.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 19 February 1941, a [[Dornier Do 17]]P (reference: 4175) from ''3./(F) 123'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]]. 30% destroyed.\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 20 February 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 52]]A-5 (reference: 466) from ''5./(F) 122'' crashed at [[Jersey Airport]] following damage from enemy [[Supermarine Spitfire]] fire. 25% damage. One wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luftwaffedata.co.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Aufkl._Gr._122_Feb_1941 |title=February 1941 |publisher=luftwaffedata.co.uk |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} In February 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 52]] crashed at [[Jersey Airport]].\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 10 March 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]F from ''5 (F)/122'' (reference: 0390) collided at [[Jersey Airport]] suffering 50% damage with another [[Junkers Ju 88]]F-5 (F)/122, suffering 80% damage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luftwaffedata.co.uk/wiki/index.php?title=Aufkl._Gr._122_Feb_1941 |title=March 1941 |publisher=luftwaffedata.co.uk |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 14 March 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A from ''3 (F)/123'' (reference: 0559) crashed at [[La Corbi\u00e8re]] [[Jersey]], crew KIA. 100% loss.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 11/12 April 1941, a [[Hawker Hurricane]] on a night intruder operation ran out of fuel, the pilot bailed out and landed on [[Lihou]] [[Guernsey]] and became a prisoner of war.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tomahawkfilms.com/blog/?p=6114 |title=A Hurricane Downed over Guernsey..! |publisher=tomahawkfilms |accessdate=22 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103700/http://tomahawkfilms.com/blog/?p=6114 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Ibeg\">{{cite book |first=William |last=Bell |title=I beg to report |publisher=Bell (1995) |ISBN=978-0952047919}}</ref>{{rp|93}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 3 October 1941, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-5 collided with another Ju 88 at [[Jersey Airport]], crew OK.\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 29 December 1941, a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]F-2 crashed at [[Saint Ouen, Jersey]] following engine failure, pilot OK.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 2 January 1942, an aircraft crashed in Bouley Bay [[Jersey]] after being shot down by an RAF plane.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 24 June 1942, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]]A-2 (reference: 5291) from ''III. /JG 2'' was rammed by a landing aircraft at [[Guernsey Airport]]. 30% damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 24 October 1942, an [[Avro Lancaster]] from ''207 Sqdn'' came down 10 miles north of [[Guernsey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 2 November 1942, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] from ''234 Sqdn'', came down close to [[Alderney]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 18 November 1942, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] Vb (reference: EN830), was hit by Flak over France and crash landed on [[Jersey]] in a turnip field. The [[Free French]] pilot waited with locals for the Germans to arrive and was captured.<ref>{{cite book |first=John |last=Lewis |title=A Doctor\u2019s Occupation |publisher= Starlight Publishing (1997) |ISBN= 978-0952565918}}</ref>{{rp|91}} The aircraft was recovered and freighted to [[Germany]] where the aircraft was tested using a German engine designed for a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://defenceoftherealm.wordpress.com/2014/11/17/the-franken-spitfire/ |title=The Franken-Spitfire |publisher=defenceoftherealm |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717055850/https://defenceoftherealm.wordpress.com/2014/11/17/the-franken-spitfire/ |archive-date=17 July 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 23 November 1942, an [[Avro Lancaster]] (reference: W4107) from ''[[No. 49 Squadron RAF]]'', crash-landed in the field opposite Seigneurie farm on [[Sark]], having run out of fuel. They thought they were landing in the Isle of Wight. All the crew were survivors, other crew having bailed out over France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.49squadron.co.uk/personnel_index/detail/Singleton_EJ |title=22/23 November, 1942; STUTTGART: |publisher=49 Squadron Association |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Marshall |first=Michael |publisher=Paramount-Lithoprint |title=Hitler envaded Sark |isbn= |year=1967}}</ref>{{rp|22}} <ref name=GFCiaW/><ref name=WFTLR/>{{rp|135}}\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 7 December 1942, a [[Westland Whirlwind (reference P6987)]] from [[No. 263 Squadron RAF]] crashed, after flying through heavy flak, south of [[Jersey]] after attacking shipping in St. Helier harbour.<ref name=\"Whirlwind\">{{cite web |url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/laurieburley/jeff/pdfs/air271550history42.pdf |title=NO. 263 SQUADRON. |publisher=ntlworld.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125833/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/laurieburley/jeff/pdfs/air271550history42.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Foreman |first=John |title=RAF fighter command victory claims Jan 41-Jun 43 |publisher=Red Kite |ISBN=978-0954620158 }}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/><ref name=WFTLR/>{{rp|135}}\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 7 December 1942, a [[Westland Whirlwind (reference P7105)]] from ''[[No. 263 Squadron RAF]]'' piloted by the Sqdn Leader was hit by flak and ditched south of [[Jersey]] after attacking shipping. The pilot was killed.<ref name=\"Whirlwind\"/><ref name=WFTLR/>{{rp|135}}\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 25 January 1943, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] from ''[[No. 541 Squadron RAF]]'' came down close to [[Guernsey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 10 April 1943, a [[Vickers Wellington]] from ''431 Sqdn'', came down in [[Saint Ouen, Jersey]] bay.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 13 June 1943, a [[Lockheed Ventura]] (reference: AE937 SB-E) from ''[[No. 464 Squadron RAAF]]'' was shot down by a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] close to [[Guernsey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafdavidstowmoor.org/crash-log/view-1943-crash-log/ |title=1943 log |publisher=rafdavidstowmoor.org |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 13 June 1943, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] II from ''[[No. 276 Squadron RAF]]'' was shot down by a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] and crashed, the pilot paddled ashore in [[Jersey]].\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 13 June 1943, a seaplane crashed north of [[Jersey]] on take off, after rescuing downed British pilot, crew hurt.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 15 June 1943, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] (reference: BR319 YQ-C) from [[No. 616 Squadron RAF]], on an anti shipping patrol, crashed north of [[Sark]]<ref name=\"M483\" >{{cite web|url=http://funautical.blogspot.com/2011/04/m-class-minesweeper-m483.html |title=15 June 1943 |publisher=funautical.blogspot.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 15 June 1943, a [[Westland Whirlwind (fighter)|Westland Whirlwind]] (reference: P7000) from [[No. 263 Squadron RAF]] exploded in flames and crashed, after sinking a German Minesweeper M483, north of [[Sark]]<ref name=\"M483\" />\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 15 June 1943, a [[Dornier Do 18]] seaplane crashes on take off at [[Saint Helier]] [[Jersey]], the Pilot broke both legs.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 25 July 1943, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] A-4 (reference: 703) from 1. /NAGr. 13 was damaged following engine trouble. 20% damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 14 August 1943, a [[Heinkel He 111]] was shot down by a[[Westland Whirlwind (fighter)]] from [[No. 263 Squadron RAF]] north of [[Guernsey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eregbaker.info/ww2_1943.htm |title=14 August 1943 |publisher=eregbaker |accessdate=24 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 23 August 1943, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] A-3 (reference: 304) from ''2. NAGr./13'' was shot down by friendly flak over [[Herm]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 7 September 1943, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] A-3 (reference: 351) from ''2. /NAGr. 12'' Overturned on landing due to pilot error. 75% damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 31 December 1943, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] IIRC \"Speed Ball\" from 511th BS of the 351st Bomb Groupcrashed west of [[Guernsey]] 8 KIA, Two were picked up next morning and made POW's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_mia_aircraft.php?acgroup_id=49&mission_date=1943-12-31 |title=#42-29877 - B-17F |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_one_acgroup.php?acgroup_id=49 |title=42-29877 |publisher=8thafhs.com}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 31 December 1943, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] IIRC \"Piccadilly Commando\" from 508th BS of the 351st Bomb Group ditched west of [[Guernsey]] 11 were rescued from a reef and became POW's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_mia_aircraft.php?acgroup_id=49&mission_date=1943-12-31 |title=#42-29630 - B-17F |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.8thafhs.com/get_one_acgroup.php?acgroup_id=49 |title=42-29630 |publisher=8thafhs.com}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 27/28 January 1944, an [[Avro Lancaster]] from 61 Sqdn crashed north of [[Guernsey]] <ref name=\"aircrew\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.aircrewremembered.com/list-of-pages-relating-to-1939-1945.html |title=Allied Archive Reports relating to 1939 - 1945 |publisher=aircrewremembered.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 7 February 1944, a [[North American P-51 Mustang|Mustang P-51B]] of the ''354th Pioneer Mustang Group'', 355th Fighter Squadron, 9th US Army Air Force, escorting bombers back from a raid on Germany was badly damaged and off course when he was shot down by flak over [[Saint Ouen, Jersey]]. The pilot bailed out and was injured on landing then captured, becoming a prisoner of war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theislandwiki.org/index.php/Mustang_crashes_in_St_Ouen%27s_Bay |title=Mustang crashes in St Ouen's Bay |publisher=theIslandwiki |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 28 February 1944, a [[Hawker Typhoon]] from [[No. 247 Squadron RAF]] came down close to [[Guernsey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 7 March 1944, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]]A-4 (reference: 7099) from ''9./JG 2'' crashed at La Ponchez, [[Castel, Guernsey]] Pilot KIA.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 19 March 1944, a [[Heinkel He 177]] was shot down by a [[Bristol Beaufighter]] SW of [[Guernsey]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 23 March 1944, a [[Focke-Wulf Fw 190]] was shot up as it came in to land at [[Guernsey Airport]], slight damage.\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} In April 1944, a [[Junkers Ju 88]] was shot down by a night fighter off [[Alderney]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 6 April 1944, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-4 crashed at Eden Chapel, St Martin [[Jersey]] Shot down in error by flak Crew x 4 KIA.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 23 April 1944, an unknown aircraft washed ashore La Rocque [[Jersey]]\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 14/15 May 1944, a [[Junkers Ju 88]]A-2 of ''I/KG 2'' was shot down by a [[Bristol Beaufighter]] from [[No. 604 Squadron RAF]], crashing into the sea off [[Guernsey]], the crew bailed out and was rescued.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] In June 1944 a carrier borne [[Grumman F6F Hellcat]] crashed after being hit by flak on the beach north of [[Herm]] The pilot became a prisoner of war.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 2 June 1944, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] (reference: MB843) from [[No. 41 Squadron RAF]] on an early morning shipping reconnaissance to Peter Point, Guernsey, then on to St Malo. Shot down by Flak from Brehon Tower near Guernsey. Hit in the radiator. The American RAFVR pilot bailed out 4 to 6 miles northeast of Guernsey and became a POW.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=90247 |title=02-JUN-1944 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 5 June 1944, a [[Hawker Typhoon]] from ''439 Sqdn'' crashed close to the [[Saint Peter Port]] harbour mouth.<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 7 June 1944, a [[Supermarine Spitfire]] reference: MB881) from [[No. 41 Squadron RAF]] escorting Typhoons on a shipping strike against [[Saint Peter Port]], it was hit by flak. The pilot bailed out of the aircraft which crashed into the sea SE [[Sark]], attempted recovery failed and he did not survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=90254 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 8 June 1944 a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] \"Our Captain\" from [[534th Bombardment Squadron]], part of 381 BG, on mission 131 was hit by flak and losing height ditched 30 miles west of [[Jersey]]. Two [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s located the crew in their rafts, followed by a [[Vickers Wellington]] which dropped a motor boat by parachute, enabling the crew to make their safe escape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.armyairforces.com/381st-Bombardment-Group-Missions-and-News-Coverage-m232309-p15.aspx |title=381st Bombardment Group Mission #131 \u2013 La Frilliere (near Tours), France (6/8/44) |publisher=armyairforces.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 11 June 1944, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] crashed five miles north west of Grand Havre, [[Guernsey]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://guernseypress.com/news/2014/05/30/fisherman-pulls-bombers-propeller-from-sea-bed/ |title=Fisherman pulls bomber\u2019s propeller from  sea bed |publisher=Guernsey Press |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=#42-97693 - B-17G |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 14 June 1944, a [[Hawker Typhoon]] (registered: MN661) from ''263 squadron'' crashed on [[Jersey]], the Belgian [[Henri Gonay|pilot]] was killed.<ref name=\"aircrew\" /><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 19 June 1944, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] F \"Idiot's Delight\" was hit by Flak from [[Alderney]] and ditched in the sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=#42-30301 - B-17F |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 20 June 1944, a [[Heinkel He 111]] crashed in flames at Samar\u00e8s [[Jersey]].<ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} {{flagicon|Luftwaffe}} On 21 June 1944 a German bomber was hit by flak from a St Peter Port flak ship and crashed, the crew of 5 all died.\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 17 July 1944 a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] G from [[545th Bombardment Squadron]] part of 384 BG, crash landed, en route to France, in [[Guernsey]]. The aircraft was salvaged on 12 June 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=#43-37971 - B-17G |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 27 July 1944, an [[Avro Lancaster]] crashed into the sea east of Essex Castle. No boat was sent out from Braye harbour and no assistance was provided to try rescuing the crew.<ref name=\"WFTLR\">{{cite book |last= Fowler |first=Will |title=The Last Raid: The Commandos, Channel Islands and Final Nazi Raid |publisher=The History Press |ISBN=978-0750966375}}</ref>{{rp|136}}\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:RAF roundel.svg|20px|Roundel]] On 9/10 August 1944, a [[Short Stirling]] (reference:EF256) from ''620 Sqdn'' on Operation Ditcher, ditched into the sea after being hit by anti-aircraft fire between [[Jersey]] and the French coast. The crew of 7 survived but 2 paratroopers from 3[[Special Air Service|SAS]] drowned.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://harringtonmuseum.org.uk/Aircraft%20lost%20on%20Allied%20Forces%20Special%20Duty%20Operations.pdf/ |title=Aircraft lost on Allied Force\u2019s Special Duty Operations & Associated Roll of Honour |publisher=harringtonmuseum.org.uk |accessdate=23 Aug 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919065451/http://www.harringtonmuseum.org.uk/Aircraft%20lost%20on%20Allied%20Forces%20Special%20Duty%20Operations.pdf |archive-date=19 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] On 30 October 1944, a [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain]] already in trouble due to tech problems as it passed low over [[Jersey]] with its landing lights on as a sign of distress. Distress flares were dropped and German flak held off for a while. However, as it flew over the north coast a 20mm flak battery opened up and the plane crashed into the sea near to a small harbour. There was only one survivor.<ref>cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?139130 |name=Douglas C-47 Dakota (+1944) |publisher= wrecksite.eu |accessdate=27 Aug 2015</ref><ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} [[File:US roundel 1943-1947.svg|30px]] 7 January 1945, a [[Lockheed P-38 Lightning]] crashed into the cliffs at Beauport, SW of [[Jersey]], the wounded pilot, Lt Moutray, was rescued from St Brelades Bay.<ref>{{cite book |first=Joe |last=Mi\u00e8re |title=Never to be forgotten |publisher=Channel Island Publishing |ISBN=978-0954266981}}</ref>{{rp|120}} <ref name=GFCiaW/>\n\n===Post War===\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 13 June 1945, a [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] (reference: P-47D) from [[544th Bombardment Squadron]], part of 384th BG, being used as a transport for demobilized personnel, suffered a landing accident at [[Guernsey Airport]] with damage rated as level 3 on a scale of 0-5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.8thafhs.com/search.php |title=1945-06-13 |publisher=8thafhs.com |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} 14 June 1947, an [[Airspeed Consul]], (registration: G-AHMC), operated by [[Westminster Airways]] crashed on landing at [[Jersey Airport]]. The aircraft was repaired and remained airworthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abpic.co.uk/photo/1115309/ |title=Airspeed AS.65 Consul, G-AHMC |publisher=abpic.co.uk |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1950s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 5 February 1951 an [[Avro Anson]] 652A (registration: G-AIXZ) undershot the [[Jersey Airport]] on approaching in fog. The aircraft was carrying national newspapers. The pilot and co-pilot survived but the aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=28298 |title=05-FEB-1951 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:DH.89A Rapide G-AGWR Morton AS RWY 16.07.50 edited-2.jpg|thumb|Rapide G-AGWR]]\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} In 1951 a [[de Havilland Dragon Rapide]] DH89A (registration: G-AGWR) operated by [[Morton Air Services]], overshot the runway and ended up near the Airport boundary. The aircraft survived and was subsequently re-registered in Norway, and after that, in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oy-reg.dk/register/2355.html |title=OY-DYA |publisher=oy-reg.dk}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 15 September 1954, a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Short Sunderland]] MR.5 (registration: PP122) hit a submerged rock on landing causing a rupture in the hull. It sank at [[Saint Peter Port]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19540915-0 |title=15 September 1954 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 2 November 1957, a [[Royal Air Force]] [[Vickers Valetta]] T.3 (registration: WJ470) hit an embankment and a building, causing the undercarriage to collapse on landing at [[Guernsey Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19571102-2 |title=Saturday 2 November 1957 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 15 August 1958, a [[Jersey Airlines]] [[de Havilland Heron]] (registration: G-AMYU) crash-landed on the grass next to the runway at Guernsey Airport and stopped on the road. Sole pilot was uninjured. Aircraft damaged beyond repair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19580815-2 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1960s==\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 1 November 1961, a [[Silver City Airways]] [[Bristol Freighter]] Coming from [[Cherbourg \u2013 Maupertus Airport]] crashed on aborting approach, due to malfunctioning of the automatic pitch coarsening unit of the starboard propeller, killing the two pilots with the other 8 occupants surviving.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19611101-0 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 26 September 1963, a [[British United Air Ferries]] [[Bristol Superfreighter]] (registration:G-AMWA) overran runway 28 at Guernsey Airport after engine problems. None of the 3 crew and 1 passenger was injured but the aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19630924-0 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 14 April 1965, [[British United Airways Flight 1030X]] [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|Douglas Dakota]] (registration:G-ANTB) crashed near [[Jersey Airport]] after a flight from [[Paris]], killing 27 passengers and crew of the 28 people on board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19650414-0&lang=en |title=14 April 1965 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 26 August 1966, a private [[Piper PA-20 Pacer|Piper PA-22-160]], (registration:G-ARXK) stalled while turning on its final approach to the aerodrome, crashing into the sea, 200 yards from Alderney, where the pilot and two passengers drowned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://143.95.41.247/wikibase/wiki.php?id=82736 |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 29 May 1969, a [[United States Air Force]], [[Lockheed Hercules]] (registration:63-7789) on an illegal flight that took off from [[RAF Mildenhall]] was allegedly shot down by two [[F-100 Super Sabre]] aircraft 30 miles north of [[Alderney]], killing the only pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19690523-2&lang=en |title=Accident description |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1970s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 6 August 1970, a [[Beagle B.206]], (registration: G-AVAM) crashed at Corbi\u00e8re after taking off from [[Jersey Airport]], killing the pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/11-1972-g-avam-6-august-1970 |title=11/1972 G-AVAM, 6 August 1970 |publisher=gov.uk |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 24 December 1974, [[British Island Airways]] Flight 185, a [[Handley Page Dart Herald]], (registration: G-BBXJ) was in a landing accident at [[Jersey Airport]] after a flight from [[Southampton]]. None of the 53 passengers and crew were harmed in the accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19741224-0 |title=Tuesday 24 December 1974 |publisher=AirSafety Network |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 14 September 1975, a [[Vickers Viscount]] on a charter flight from East Midlands (registration: G-AZNH) made a heavy landing that caused the nose wheel to collapse. None of the 78 passengers or crew were harmed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vickersviscount.net/Index/VickersViscount342History.aspx |title=14 September 1975 |publisher=vickersviscount.net}}</ref>\n\n==1980s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 1 October 1980, a private [[Cessna Citation]] (registration: G-BPCP) crashed on approach to [[Jersey Airport]], killing the only pilot who was on a flight from [[Cardiff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/4-1982-cessna-citation-500-g-bpcp-1-october-1980 |title= 4/1982 Cessna Citation 500, G-BPCP, 1 October 1980 |publisher=GOV.UK |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 18 September 1981, a [[Jersey European Airways]] Flight 245 [[Britten-Norman Islander]] (registration: G-BDNP) on a flight from [[Jersey Airport]] to [[Guernsey Airport]] crashed on approach when one of the engines stopped. The pilot tried to land at Guernsey Airport but failed and then attempted to land in a field but crashed into a stone wall. None of the 9 passengers or crew were killed in the accident, however the pilot was badly injured. The pilot had intended to fly a version of the Islander with fuel tanks on the tips of the wings, but due to technical problems took another plane. Thus the engine ran out of fuel, stopped and caused the accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19810918-2 |title= accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 3 October 1981, a private fight [[Partenavia P.68]] (registration: EC-DHE) on a flight from [[Cardiff Airport]] to [[Alicante\u2013Elche Airport]] Aircraft was on a night IFR flight when one of the engines failed. Pilot could not maintain height and eventually crashed into the sea 5m SE off Guernsey. (The aircraft was never found) None of the 5 occupants survived.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=1076 |title= ASN Wikibase Occurrence # 1076 |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 16 September 1982, a private fight [[Wassmer WA-40|Wassmer WA-41]] (reference: G-BAGM) crashed into the sea 20 miles north of [[Alderney]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airport-data.com/aircraft/G-BAGM.html |title= G-BAGM |publisher=airport-data.com |accessdate=25 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==1990s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 23 May 1995, a [[Brymon Airways]] [[Bombardier Dash 8]] (registration: G-BRYJ) tail struck the runway 27 at [[Jersey Airport]]. The incident caused some damage to the tail of the aircraft. None of the 4 crew and 44 passengers were injured in the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/De%20Havilland%20Canada%20DHC-8-311%20Dash%208,%20G-BRYJ%2007-95.pdf |title=De Havilland Canada DHC-8-311 Dash8, G-BTYJ |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 7 December 1997, an [[AirUK]] F-27-500F (registration: G-BNCY) a flight from [[Southampton Airport]] to [[Guernsey Airport]] was involved in a landing accident at Guernsey Airport. The aircraft overran runway 27 while landing in high (34 kt) crosswinds and came to rest in an adjacent field with its left landing gear collapsed. There were no injuries among the 50 passengers and 4 crew. (The aircraft was damaged beyond repair and subsequently written off.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/publications/formal_reports/4_1999_g_bncy.cfm |title=Report No: 4/1999. Report on the accident to Fokker F27-500, G-BNCY, at Guernsey Airport, Channel Islands on 7 December 1997 |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 12 June 1998, a private [[Piper PA-31 Navajo]] (registration: CN-TFP) on a flight from [[Tangier]] to [[Iceland]]. The pilot was going to refuel in [[France]] but kept on flying to Guernsey. As the aircraft was over the Channel islands the aircraft ran out of fuel and the pilot ditched the aircraft into the sea just north-west of [[Jersey]]. The accident killed the only pilot on the aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/publications/formal_reports/2_1999_cn_tfp.cfm |title=Report No: 2/1999. Report on the accident to Piper PA-31-350, CN-TFP, north-west of Jersey, Channel Islands on 12 June 1998 |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 12 January 1999, a [[Channel Express]] F-27-600F (registration: G-CHNL) cargo flight from [[London Luton Airport]] to [[Guernsey Airport]] was incorrectly loaded affecting centre of gravity, stalled on approach to the airport, crashed, and caught fire. The fire spread to two nearby homes, killing the pilots and injuring one person on the ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19990112-0 |title=Report accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 5 June 2001, a [[Channel Express]] cargo flight from [[Jersey Airport]] to [[Bournemouth Airport]] but just minutes after take off engine one caught fire. The [[Fokker F-27 Friendship]] landed back at Jersey and none of the 3 crew were injured.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20010605-0 | work=Aviation Safety Network | title= 5 Jun 2001 | accessdate=23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Sark}} On 13 October 2001, a [[Europa XS]] 912 light aircraft, registered G-BWGH flying from [[Jersey Airport]] suffered engine failure and crash landed on [[Little Sark]]. The two occupants were uninjured. The aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=173880 | work=Aviation Safety Network | title=13 Oct 2001 | accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 8 March 2006, a HS748 Series 2a registered G-BVOV overran the runway at [[Guernsey Airport]]. There were no injuries. The cause of the accident was that the flight crew did not operate the propeller controls correctly, meaning that less drag was created than would have been had the controls been operated correctly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/publications/formal_reports/6_2008_g_bvov.cfm |title=Report on the serious incident to Hawker Siddeley HS 748 Series 2A, G-BVOV at Guernsey Airport, Channel Islands on 8 March 2006 |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> The aircraft body now rests in a quarry in Capernwray, Lancashire where it is used by divers.\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 23 August 2009, a private [[Piper Saratoga]] (registration: G-BTCA) crashed due to turbulence caused by nearby cliffs on approach to [[Alderney Airport]]. The pilot and 3 passengers sustained minor injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/Piper%20PA-32R-300%20Cherokee%20Lance,%20G-BTCA%2002-10.pdf |title=Piper PA-32R-300 Cherokee Lance, g-BTCA |publisher=UK AAIB |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref>\n\n==2010s==\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 12 November 2011, a [[Piper PA-28 Cherokee|Piper PA-28-181 Archer II]] (registration: G-BXRG) owned by Alderney Flying Training Ltd. ditched in the sea near the Casquettes, 25 miles northwest of Alderney. The reason for the accident is not yet known. Of the two occupants in the aircraft, the passenger was rescued by a merchant ship. The pilot has not been found.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-15710937 | work=BBC News | title=Alderney aircraft crash: Search called off for man | date=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 27 March 2012, a [[Britten-Norman Trislander]] BN2A MK.III-2 (registration: G-BDTO) owned by Aurigny Air Services on a flight from [[Alderney Airport]] to [[Southampton]] suffered an engine failure, the aircraft returned safely to [[Alderney]] .<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/bn2a-mk-iii-2-trislander-g-bdto-27-march-2012 | work=GOV.UK | title=BN2A MK.III-2 Trislander, G-BDTO, 27 March 2012 | accessdate=23 Aug 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 16 June 2012, an [[ATR 42]] (registration: G-DRFC) owned by [[Blue Islands]] suffered an undercarriage failure on landing. No one was hurt but the aircraft was written off.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-jersey-18476461 |title=Jersey Airport Blue Island plane crash probe begins |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Jersey}} On 3 November 2013, a [[Britten-Norman Islander]] BN2B-21 (registration: G-CIAS) owned by Channel Islands Air Search on a search and rescue mission flight from [[Guernsey Airport]] suffered fuel problems resulting in a crash landing on the north coast of [[Jersey]]. There were no injuries.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.gov.uk/aaib-reports/s8-2013-bn2b-21-islander-3-november-2013 | work=GOV.UK | title=S8/2013 BN2B-21 Islander,, 3 November 2013 | accessdate= 23 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Guernsey}} On 17 June 2014, a [[SOCATA TB family|Socata TB10]] (registration: G-POPI) taking off from [[Guernsey Airport]] suffered a mechanical failure and struck a greenhouse shortly after becoming airborne. The aircraft was written off. There were no injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-27926178 |title=Guernsey plane crash pilot 'lucky to be alive' |publisher=Guernsey press |accessdate=22 Aug 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{flagicon|Alderney}} On 21 January 2019, a [[Piper PA-46]] (registration: N264DB) disappeared from radar screens and [[2019 Piper PA-46 Malibu crash|crashed]] near [[Les Casquets]], 8 miles north-west of [[Alderney]]. Argentinian footballer [[Emiliano Sala]] was aboard the aircraft, which was flying from [[Nantes Atlantique Airport|Nantes]] to [[Cardiff Airport|Cardiff]]. The wreckage of the aircraft was found thirteen days later on the seabed at a depth of 220 feet (67 m). On 7 February, Sala's body was recovered from the wreckage. No trace of the pilot was found.\n\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*Doyle, Neville. 1991. From Sea-Eagle to Flamingo: Channel Islands Airlines 1923-1939. {{ISBN|1-85421-103-X}}\n*{{cite book | last = Pinnegar | first = Edward  | pages = 128 |year = July 2010 |title = A History of Aviation in Alderney |publisher = Amberley Publishing, Stroud |isbn = 978-1-84868-981-7 }}\n\n